# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: achim-großmann
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 27 September 1998 to elect the members of the 14th Bundestag.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic Party (SPD) emerged as the largest faction in parliament for the first time since 1972, with its leader Gerhard Schröder becoming chancellor.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The Christian Democrats had their worst election result since 1949.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Since German reunification on 3 October 1990, the unemployment rate in Germany had risen from 4.2% to 9.4% in 1998, with the Federal Labor Office registering more than 4 million unemployed.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The unified Germany had to fight economic and domestic difficulties even as it actively participated in the project of European integration.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Most people blamed the centre-right coalition government of the Christian Democratic Union/Christian Social Union (CDU/CSU) and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) for the economic difficulties.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Longtime Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government was regarded by many as not having fully implemented the unification after eight years, in view of the mass protests in many eastern German towns due to job losses and social welfare cuts.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The 1998 campaign began with both the CDU and SPD working out who would lead their parties.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] There had been rumours that Kohl would resign and allow Wolfgang Schäuble to take the reins of the CDU, but these rumours were rendered obsolete when Kohl announced in April 1997 that he would seek the chancellorship for a sixth term.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The two contenders for the SPD nomination were Oskar Lafontaine, the party's chairman, and Gerhard Schröder, Minister-President of Lower Saxony.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] On 1 March 1998, Schröder led the SPD to a huge victory in the Lower Saxony state election, gaining an unusual absolute majority for the second time and effectively receiving the SPD nomination for federal chancellor.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Schröder had announced he would withdraw his bid for the nomination if he received below 42 percent of the popular vote.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] In the 1998 general elections, Schröder received 47.9 percent.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Following this election, Lafontaine withdrew his bid and Schröder was inaugurated in the May 1998 convention.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] For the SPD, Schröder offered a new face for the party.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] He gave the party a new vigor, one that was lacking in the CDU after Kohl proclaimed his nomination.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Many in the CDU questioned if Kohl had made the right choice for the party.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU campaign was based on the experience and reputation of Kohl.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] One of the CDU's main slogans was 'Safety, not Risks.' "Kohl exploited his familiarity and experience, as well as his status as Europe's longest serving head of government." The SPD on the other hand ran the campaign using strategies developed in the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD set up election headquarters and introduced 'rapid rebuttal units' not unlike those used by Bill Clinton of the United States in his successful presidential bid in 1992.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD avoided direct attacks at Kohl, but rather focused on their message of a "new center".
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The FDP had usually ridden on the coattails of the CDU, and was mostly disapproved in the polls.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] With the SPD well ahead in the polls, many of the voters from the CDU had fewer incentives to vote for the FDP.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The FDP was also having trouble projecting a coherent platform to voters.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The Greens too were having issues concerning their platform.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The two factions in the Greens, the fundamentalists and the pragmatists, had problems settling on their platform since the founding of the Green party.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The major issue of the 1998 campaign was unemployment.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] In 1996, the unemployment rate in Germany surpassed the government's "limit" of 4 million unemployed people.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Both parties blamed high labor costs, high taxes and the high welfare costs as the causes of the problem.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] During the campaign, Schröder used this issue against Kohl, calling him 'the unemployment chancellor.' Unemployment was worst in the former East Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] While the national rate stood at 9.4 percent, former East Germany was suffering with unemployment at 20 percent.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Many in the former East Germany blamed Kohl for the slow economic recovery.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Another issue at hand were Germany's tax and welfare reforms.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] While the CDU/CSU had offered proposals to reduce benefits in healthcare and pensions, the SPD controlled Bundesrat secured the passage of the bill.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The proposed bill also offered tax cuts that were to benefit the rich, something the SPD opposed.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] While Kohl continually pushed the issue of European integration, the issue fell short from voters' minds.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Schröder, on the other hand, almost ignored the issue.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Many voters in Germany had other concerns besides the European Union.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Toward the end of the campaign, polls placed the CDU/CSU and FDP coalition in a tie with the SPD and Green coalition.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Despite these polls, the final numbers told a different story.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD-Green coalition won an unexpectedly large victory, taking 345 seats and earning a strong majority in the Bundestag—the first centre-left absolute majority in post-World War II Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD won 40.9 percent of the vote, due to an increase of 4.5 percent from 1994.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU-FDP coalition had gone into the election with a solid majority and 341 seats, but was cut down to 288 seats.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU lost 6.2% of its 1994 vote, and lost 109 electoral districts to the SPD.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Germany's mixed-member proportional system, in which a slate of statewide delegates are elected alongside the electorate delegates, softened the blow somewhat, so the CDU/CSU only suffered a net loss of 49 seats.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] It was still the CDU/CSU's worst defeat ever.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] By contrast, their junior coalition partner, the FDP, netted a loss of just 4 seats.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD swept all single-member constituency seats in the states of Brandenburg, Saxony-Anhalt, Saarland, Bremen, Hamburg and (for the first and last time) Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Kohl lost his own constituency of Ludwigshafen, though he was still re-elected to the Bundestag through the Rhineland-Palatinate CDU party list, and he had not won the seat in the 1983 and 1987 elections.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Future Chancellor Angela Merkel only narrowly won her constituency of Stralsund – Rügen – Grimmen with only 37.3 percent of the vote; the only time she got less than 40 percent of the vote.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] A new government was formed by a coalition between the SPD and the Greens, with the SPD's Gerhard Schröder as chancellor and Greens leader Joschka Fischer as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] It was the first red-green coalition government at the federal level in Germany, as well as the first purely centre-left government in post-World War II Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Kohl stepped down as chairman of the CDU, as did CSU chairman Theodor Waigel.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] The 1998 German election was historic in many ways.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] It resulted in a centre-right government being succeeded by a left-wing one—the first in postwar Germany (the SPD's previous term in government had been at the helm of a centre-left coalition).
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] In addition, it brought to an end the sixteen-year rule of Kohl – the second-longest of any German chancellor, and the longest tenure for a democratically elected head of government in German history.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] It has been compared to the defeat of Winston Churchill in 1945 – both were seen as conservative wartime leaders, and in both cases both were turned out of office by the electorate once the war was over.
[src:achim-großmann/1998-german-federal-election] Churchill was ousted before World War II was even over, while Kohl managed to hang onto power for two more terms after the reunification of Germany (which is often considered to be the end of the Cold War).
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 27 September 2009 to elect the members of the 17th Bundestag.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU), its Bavarian sister party, the Christian Social Union (CSU), and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) won the election, and the three parties formed a new centre-right government with Angela Merkel as chancellor.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] While CDU/CSU's share of votes decreased slightly, it was more than compensated by the gains of their "desired coalition partner", the liberal FDP, that won the strongest result in its history.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] CDU and CSU's former partner in the "Grand coalition", the Social Democratic Party (SPD) led by Frank-Walter Steinmeier, conceded defeat after dropping by more than 11 percentage points, receiving its hitherto worst result since the end of the Second World War (only undercut in 2017 and 2025).
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] At 70.8 percent, the voter turnout was the lowest in a German federal election since 1949.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] According to Article 38 of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany, members of the Bundestag shall be elected in general, direct, free, equal, and secret elections; everyone over the age of eighteen is entitled to vote.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] In 2008, some modifications to the electoral system were required under an order of the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The court had found a provision in the Federal Election Law by which it was possible for a party to experience a negative vote weight, namely losing seats due to more votes, violated the constitutional guarantee of the electoral system being equal and direct.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The court allowed three years for these changes, so the 2009 German federal election was not affected.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The changes were due by 30 June 2011 but appropriate legislation was not completed by that deadline.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] A new electoral law was enacted in late 2011 but was declared unconstitutional once again by the Federal Constitutional Court upon lawsuits from the opposition parties and a group of some 4,000 private citizens.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The Bundestag approved and enacted the new electoral reform in February 2013.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The Bundestag is elected using mixed-member proportional representation, meaning that each voter has two votes, a first vote for the election of a constituency candidate by first-past-the-post and a second vote for the election of a state list.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method is used to convert the votes into seats, in a two-stage process with each stage involving two calculations.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] First, the number of seats to be allocated to each state is calculated, based on the proportion of the German population living there.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] Then the seats in each state are allocated to the party lists in that state, based on the proportion of second votes each party received.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] In the distribution of seats among state lists, only parties that have obtained at least five percent of the valid second votes cast in the electoral area or have won a seat in at least three constituencies are taken into consideration.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The minimum number of seats for each party at federal level is then determined.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] This is done by calculating, for each party state list, the number of constituency seats it won on the basis of the first votes, as well as the number of seats to which it is entitled on the basis of the second votes.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The higher of these two figures is the party's minimum number of seats in that state.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] Adding together the minimum number of seats to which the party is entitled in all of the states produces a total representing its guaranteed minimum number of seats in the country as a whole.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] In order to ensure that each party receives its guaranteed minimum number of seats when the seats are allocated using the Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method, it may become necessary to increase the number of seats in the Bundestag.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] Then it must be ensured that the seats are distributed to the parties in line with their national share of the second votes.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] Additional overhang seats, or balance seats, are created to ensure that the distribution of the seats reflects the parties' share of the second votes and that no party receives fewer than its guaranteed minimum number of seats.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] Balance seats are also necessary to ensure that each party requires roughly the same number of second votes per seat.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] Once the number of seats which each party is entitled to receive across the country has been determined, the seats are allocated to the parties' individual state lists.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] Each state list must receive at least as many seats as the number of constituencies which the party won in the state in question.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] Since the 2005 election, Chancellor Angela Merkel (CDU) had governed in a grand coalition with the SPD.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] However, it was her stated goal to win a majority for CDU/CSU and FDP (the CDU/CSU's traditional coalition partner) in 2009.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] Foreign minister and Vice-Chancellor Frank-Walter Steinmeier (SPD) was formally nominated as his party's chancellor-candidate at a convention on 18 October 2008.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] He aimed to form a government in which the SPD was the strongest party, but which also excluded the left-socialist party The Left.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The election campaign was considered exceptionally boring, which may be attributable to a perceived lack of charisma on the part of the leaders of the CDU and SPD.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] Another reason pointed to for the sedate campaign is that the CDU and SPD both defended the record of their grand coalition, and facing the possibility of having to continue the grand coalition in a friendly manner.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] Merkel was content with the low-key campaign style, which was largely seen as benefiting her party because of her high approval ratings.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] CDU candidate Vera Lengsfeld released a campaign poster featuring herself and Merkel in a way that emphasised their cleavage.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The poster bore the slogan "We have more to offer" (German: "*Wir haben mehr zu bieten*").
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] On 23 September 2009, four days before the federal elections, German police raided the Berlin headquarters of the National Democratic Party of Germany NPD to investigate claims that letters sent from the NPD to politicians from immigrant backgrounds incited racial hatred.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The federal election was the final and most important election in what is called a *Superwahljahr* (super election year) in Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU and FDP, with an average vote share of around 50% in pre-election polling during the weeks before the election, were clearly ahead of the other traditional coalition partners in Germany, SPD and the Greens.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU received a slightly lower proportion than in the previous election, with the Bavarian CSU receiving its lowest vote share in decades.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] Overall, the CDU/CSU had their worst vote share in 60 years.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] In contrast, their preferred coalition partner, the liberal FDP, gained nearly 5% points to give it 14.6% of the vote, the best result of its history.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The big loser of the election was the SPD, which received its worst result ever in a federal election, receiving only 23% of the total party vote and suffering the biggest percentage loss of any party in German federal election history in 60 years.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] The two other parties represented in the Bundestag, the Left and the Greens, both made large gains and received the highest vote share of their respective histories.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] For the first time, The Left won constituency seats outside its traditional stronghold of East Berlin.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] As a result of the losses by the SPD and the gains by the FDP, the alliance of the CDU/CSU and FDP received an outright majority of seats, ensuring that Angela Merkel would continue as chancellor.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] Had the CDU/CSU and FDP failed to win a majority of seats, possible alternative coalitions may have included a continuation of the grand coalition of CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:achim-großmann/2009-german-federal-election] A traffic light coalition (SPD–FDP–Greens) was specifically ruled out by FDP leader Guido Westerwelle.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The once Celtic settlement was equipped with several *thermae* in the course of colonization by Roman pioneers settling at the warm Aachen thermal springs around the 1st century.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] After the withdrawal of the Roman troops, the vicus *Aquae Granni* was Frankized around the 5th century, by which it came under Merovingian and later Carolingian rule.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] With the completion of the Carolingian Palace of Aachen at the transition to the 9th century, Aachen was constituted as the main royal residence of the Frankish Empire ruled by Charlemagne.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Because of that, the city is sometimes called the "cradle of Europe".
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] After the Treaty of Verdun, the city was within the borders of Middle Francia, until it became part of East Francia after the Treaty of Meerssen (870).
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] It subsequently was part of the Holy Roman Empire and was granted city rights in 1166 by Emperor Frederick Barbarossa, becoming an imperial city.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] It served as the coronation site where 31 Holy Roman Emperors were crowned Kings of the Germans from 936 to 1531, until Frankfurt became the preferred place of coronation.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] One of Germany's leading institutes of higher education in technology, the RWTH Aachen University *(Rheinisch-Westfälisch Technische Hochschule Aachen)*, is located in the city.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Its university hospital Uniklinikum Aachen is Europe's largest single-building hospital.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen's industries include science, engineering and information technology.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In 2009, Aachen was ranked eighth among cities in Germany for innovation.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen is located at the northern foothills of the High Fens and the Eifel Mountains.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] It sits on the Wurm River, a tributary of the Rur, and together with Mönchengladbach, it is the only larger German city in the drainage basin of the Meuse.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The regional dialect spoken in the city is a Central Franconian, Ripuarian variant with strong Limburgish influences from the dialects in the neighbouring Netherlands.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] As a Rhenish city, Aachen is one of the main centres of carnival celebrations in Germany, along with Cologne and Mainz.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The culinary specialty for which the city is best known is Aachener Printen, a type of gingerbread.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The name *Aachen* is a modern descendant, like southern German *Ach(e)*, German: *Aach*, meaning "river" or "stream", from Old High German *ahha*, meaning "water" or "stream", which directly translates (and etymologically corresponds) to Latin *Aquae*, referring to the springs.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The location has been inhabited by humans since the Neolithic era, about 5,000 years ago, attracted to its warm mineral springs.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Latin *Aquae* figures in Aachen's Roman name *Aquae granni*, which meant "waters of Grannus", referring to the Celtic god of healing who was worshipped at the springs.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] This word became *Åxhe* in Walloon and *Aix* in French, and subsequently *Aix-la-Chapelle* to distinguish it from Aix-en-Provence, after Charlemagne had his palatine chapel built there in the late 8th century and then made the city his empire's capital.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Flint quarries on the Lousberg, Schneeberg, and Königshügel, first used during Neolithic times (3000–2500 BC), attest to the long occupation of the site of Aachen, as do recent finds under the modern city's *Elisengarten* pointing to a former settlement from the same period.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Bronze Age (around 1600 BC) settlement is evidenced by the remains of barrows (burial mounds) found, for example, on the Klausberg.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] During the Iron Age, the area was settled by Celtic peoples who were perhaps drawn by the marshy Aachen basin's hot sulphur springs where they worshipped Grannus, god of light and healing.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Proofs of a Celts settlements on Aachens territories at the beginning of the Gallic War do not exist at the moment.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The 25-hectare Roman spa resort town of Aquae Granni was, according to legend, founded by Grenus, under Hadrian, around 124 AD.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Grenus refers to the Celtic god, and it seems it was the Roman 6th Legion at the start of the 1st century AD that first channelled the hot springs into a spa at Büchel, adding at the end of the same century the *Münstertherme* spa, two water pipelines, and a probable sanctuary dedicated to Grannus.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] A kind of forum, surrounded by colonnades, connected the two spa complexes.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] There was an extensive residential area.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The Romans built bathhouses near Burtscheid.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] A temple precinct called *Vernenum* was built near the modern Kornelimünster/Walheim.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Today, remains have been found of three bathhouses, including two fountains in the *Elisenbrunnen* and the Burtscheid bathhouse.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Roman civil administration in Aachen eventually broke down as the baths and other public buildings (along with most of the villae rusticae of the surrounding countryside) were destroyed around AD 375 at the start of the migration period.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The last Roman coin finds are from the time of Emperor Gratian (AD 375–383).
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Rome withdrew its troops from the area, but the town remained populated.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] By 470, the town came to be ruled by the Ripuarian Franks and subordinated to their capital, Cologne.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] During the Roman period, Aachen was the site of a flourishing Jewish community.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Pepin the Short had a castle residence built in the town, due to the proximity of the hot springs and also for strategic reasons as it is located between the Rhineland and northern France.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In the year of his coronation as king of the Franks, 768, Charlemagne came to spend Christmas at Aachen for the first time.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] He remained there in a mansion which he may have extended, although there is no source attesting to any significant building activity at Aachen in his time, apart from the building of the Palatine Chapel (since 1930, cathedral) and the Palace.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Charlemagne spent most winters in Aachen between 792 and his death in 814.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen became the focus of his court and the political centre of his empire.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] During the Carolingian empire, a Jewish community lived near the royal palace.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In Jewish texts, the city of Aachen was called *Aish* or *Ash* (אש).
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In 797, Isaac, a Jewish merchant, accompanied two ambassadors of Charlemagne to the court of Harun al-Rashid.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] He returned to Aachen in July 802, bearing an elephant called Abul-Abbas as a gift for the emperor.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] By the terms of the Treaty of Verdun 834, Aachen became part of Middle Francia, governed by emperor Lothair.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] He was succeeded by Lothair II as king of Lotharingia by the terms of the Treaty of Prüm.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] By the Treaty of Meerssen 870, Aachen came to East Francia.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Within East Francia, later the Holy Roman Empire until 1166, Aachen was part of the Duchy of Lower Lotharingia.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In 936, Otto I was crowned king of East Francia in the collegiate church built by Charlemagne.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] During the reign of Otto II, the nobles revolted and the West Franks under Lothair raided Aachen in 978.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen was attacked again by Odo of Champagne, who attacked the imperial palace while Conrad II was absent.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Odo relinquished it and was killed afterwards.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The palace and town of Aachen had fortifying walls built by order of Emperor Frederick Barbarossa between 1172 and 1176.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Over the next 500 years, most kings of Germany who ruled the Holy Roman Empire were crowned in Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The original audience hall built by Charlemagne was torn down and replaced by the current city hall in 1330.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] During the 13th century, many Jews converted to Christianity, as shown in the records of the Aachen Minster (today's Cathedral).
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In 1486, the Jews of Aachen offered gifts to Maximilian I during his coronation ceremony.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The last king to be crowned here was Ferdinand I in 1531.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] During the Middle Ages, Aachen remained a city of regional importance, due to its proximity to Flanders; it achieved a modest position in the trade in woollen cloths, favoured by imperial privilege.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The city remained a free imperial city, subject to the emperor only, but was politically far too weak to influence the policies of any of its neighbours.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The only dominion it had was over Burtscheid, a neighbouring territory ruled by a Benedictine abbess, which was forced to accept that all of its traffic must pass through the "Aachener Reich".
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] As an imperial city, Aachen held certain political privileges that allowed it to remain independent of the troubles of Europe for many years.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] It remained a direct vassal of the Holy Roman Empire throughout most of the Middle Ages.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] It was also the site of many important church councils, including the Council of 837 and the Council of 1166, a council convened by the antipope Paschal III.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Parts of Aachen belonged to Imperial Abbey of Burtscheid, Reichsabtei Kornelimünster, Duchy of Juelich and the Duchy of Limburg.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen was an important site for the production of historical manuscripts.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Under Charlemagne's purview, both the Ada Gospels and the Coronation Gospels may have been produced in Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In addition, quantities of the other texts in the court library were also produced locally.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] During the reign of Louis the Pious (814–840), substantial quantities of ancient texts were produced at Aachen, including legal manuscripts such as the leges scriptorium group, patristic texts including the five manuscripts of the Bamberg Pliny Group.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Finally, under Lothair I (840–855), texts of outstanding quality were still being produced.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] This however marked the end of the period of manuscript production at Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In 1598, following the invasion of Spanish troops from the Netherlands, Rudolf deposed all Protestant office holders in Aachen and went as far as expelling them from the city.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] From the early 16th century, Aachen started to lose its power and influence.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] First the coronations of emperors were moved from Aachen to Frankfurt.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] 1614 Aachen became theatre of the Siege of Aachen (1614) within the War of the Jülich Succession.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Although religious changes were forced several times in Aachen and Protestant communities were banned, hardly any fighting took place during the Thirty Years' War.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The religious wars had been followed by the great fire of 1656.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] After the destruction of most of the city in 1656, the rebuilding was mostly in the Baroque style.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The decline of Aachen culminated in 1794, when the French, led by General Charles Dumouriez, occupied Aachen..
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The area of Aachen had been scene of battles within the Flanders Campaign in autumn 1794: Battle of Ourthe, Battle of Aldenhoven, Siege of Maastricht.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In 1542, the Dutch humanist and physician Francis Fabricius published his study of the health benefits of the hot springs in Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] By the middle of the 17th century, the city had developed a considerable reputation as a spa, although this was in part because Aachen was then – and remained well into the 19th and early 20th century – a place of high-level prostitution.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Traces of this hidden agenda of the city's history are found in the 18th-century guidebooks to Aachen as well as to the other spas.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The main indication for visiting patients, ironically, was syphilis; only by the end of the 19th century had rheumatism become the most important object of cures at Aachen and Burtscheid.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen was chosen as the site of several important congresses and peace treaties: the first congress of Aachen (often referred to as the Congress of Aix-la-Chapelle in English) on 2 May 1668, leading to the First Treaty of Aachen in the same year which ended the War of Devolution.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The second congress ended with the second treaty in 1748, ending the War of the Austrian Succession.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In 1789, there was a constitutional crisis in the Aachen government, and in 1794 Aachen lost its status as a free imperial city.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In 1629, the Aachen Jewish community was expelled from the city.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In 1667, six Jews were allowed to return.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Most of the Aachen Jewish community settled in Burtscheid.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] As recently as the late 18th century the Abbess of Burtscheid was still prevented from building a road linking her territory to the neighbouring estates of the duke of Jülich; the city of Aachen deployed its handful of soldiers to chase away road-diggers.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] On 9 February 1801, the Peace of Lunéville removed the ownership of Aachen and the entire "left bank" of the Rhine from Germany (the Holy Roman Empire) and granted it to France.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In 1815, control of the town was passed to the Kingdom of Prussia through an agreement reached by the Congress of Vienna.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The third congress took place in 1818, to decide the fate of occupied Napoleonic France.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The current territory of Aachen belonged entirely to the Arrondissement d'Aix-la-Chapelle.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In 1815, after the Second Treaty of Paris, finishing the Napoleonic Wars, the Kingdom of Prussia took over within the new German Confederation.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The city was one of its most socially and politically backward centres until the end of the 19th century.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The Kingdom of Prussia created the "Regierungsbezirk Aachen" (governmental district) and integrated it into the Prussian province Grand Duchy of the Lower Rhine, from 1822 the Rhine Province.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Starting in 1838, the railway from Cologne to Belgium passed through Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] By "Gesetz betreffend die Vereinigung der Stadtgemeinde Burtscheid mit der Stadtgemeinde Aachen vom 29.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] März 1897 nebst Vertrag" Aachen and Burtscheid merged 1897.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The city suffered extreme overcrowding and deplorable sanitary conditions until 1875, when the medieval fortifications were abandoned as a limit to building and new, better housing was built in the east of the city, where sanitary drainage was easiest.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In December 1880, the Aachen tramway network was opened, and in 1895 it was electrified.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In the 19th century and up to the 1930s, the city was important in the production of railway locomotives and carriages, iron, pins, needles, buttons, tobacco, woollen goods, and silk goods.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen was enlarged 1 April 1906 by "Gesetz betreffend die Vereinigung der Gemeinde Forst mit der Stadtgemeinde Aachen vom 31.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] März 1906 nebst Vertrag" by incorporation of Forst.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The Belgium Campaign within World War I started in Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] After World War I, Aachen was occupied by the Entente until 1930, along with the rest of German territory west of the Rhine.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen was one of the locations involved in the Rhenish Republic.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] On 21 October 1923, an armed mob took over the city hall.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Similar actions took place in Mönchengladbach, Duisburg, and Krefeld.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] During the interwar period, Aachen was assigned some areas of the former district of Eupen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Also the Western Campaign of World War II started nearby Aachen with the Battle of Maastricht.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen was heavily damaged during World War II.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Blood mentioned more than 120 air strikes on Aachen between 1940 an 1944.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] According to Jörg Friedrich in *The Fire* (2002), two Allied air raids on 11 April and 24 May 1944 "radically destroyed" the city.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The first killed 1,525, including 212 children, and bombed six hospitals.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] During the second, 442 aircraft hit two railway stations, killed 207, and left 15,000 homeless.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The raids destroyed Aachen-Eilendorf and Aachen-Burtscheid.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In autumn 1944 Aachen and its surroundings were reached by the Western Allied Siegfried Line campaign.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The city and its fortified surroundings were besieged from 12 September to 21 October 1944 by the US 1st Infantry Division with the 3rd Armored Division assisting from the south.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Around 13 October the US 2nd Armored Division, coming from the north, and got as close as Würselen, while the 30th Infantry Division completed the encirclement of Aachen on 16 October 1944.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] With reinforcements from the US 28th Infantry Division the battle continued involving direct assaults through the heavily defended city, which forced the German garrison to surrender on 21 October 1944.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen was the first German city to be captured by the Western Allies, and its residents welcomed the soldiers as liberators.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] What remained of the city was destroyed—in some areas completely—during the fighting, mostly by American artillery fire and demolitions carried out by the Waffen-SS defenders.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Damaged buildings included medieval churches and the Rathaus (city hall), although Aachen Cathedral was largely unscathed.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] 4,000 inhabitants remained in the city; the rest had followed evacuation orders.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Its first Allied-appointed mayor, Franz Oppenhoff, was assassinated by an SS commando unit.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] On 16 May 1815, the Jewish community of the city offered an homage in its synagogue to the Prussian king, Friedrich Wilhelm III.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In 1862, a large synagogue was built, later called the Old Synagogue.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] On *Kristallnacht* in 1938, the synagogue was destroyed.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] By the onset of World War II in 1939, many Jews had emigrated or were arrested, and only 782 remained in the city.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] At the end of the war in 1945, only 62 Jews lived in the city.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] As of 2003, 1,434 Jews were again living in Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Subsequent the German surrender finishing the Battle of Aachen 21 October 1944, the Supreme Headquarters Allied Expeditionary Force acted as military government.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen within the northern part of Rhine Province became part of British occupation zone in Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen also belonged to the British zone under Belgian control.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] 46, British Military Government created the "Land Nordrhein/Westfalen", including the "Regierungsbezirk Aachen", 23 August 1946.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] 23 May 1949 Aachen became part of the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] With the Aachen Law of 1971, Aachen was merged with Kornelimünster, Brand, Walheim, Laurensberg, Richterich, Haaren, Eilendorf.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] After the abolition of the Aachen governmental district, August 1972, Aachen became part of the Cologne governmental district.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen is located in the middle of the Meuse–Rhine Euroregion, close to the border tripoint of Germany, the Netherlands, and Belgium.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The town of Vaals in the Netherlands lies nearby at about 6 km (4 mi) from Aachen's city centre, while the Dutch city of Heerlen and Eupen, the capital of the German-speaking Community of Belgium, are both located about 20 km (12 mi) from Aachen city centre.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen lies near the head of the open valley of the Wurm (which today flows through the city in canalised form), part of the larger basin of the Meuse, and about 30 km (19 mi) north of the High Fens, which form the northern edge of the Eifel uplands of the Rhenish Massif.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The maximum dimensions of the city's territory are 21.6 km (13+3⁄8 mi) from north to south, and 17.2 km (10+3⁄4 mi) from east to west.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The highest point in Aachen, located in the far southeast of the city, lies at an elevation of 410 m (1,350 ft) above sea level.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The lowest point, in the north, and on the border with the Netherlands, is at 125 m (410 ft).
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] As the westernmost city in Germany (and close to the Low Countries), Aachen and the surrounding area belongs to a temperate climate zone (Cfb), with humid weather, mild winters, and warm summers.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Because of its location north of the Eifel and the High Fens and its subsequent prevailing westerly weather patterns, rainfall in Aachen (on average 805 mm/year) is comparatively higher than, for example, in Bonn (with 669 mm/year).
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Another factor in the local weather forces of Aachen is the occurrence of Foehn winds on the southerly air currents, which results from the city's geographic location on the northern edge of the Eifel.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Because the city is surrounded by hills, it suffers from inversion-related smog.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Some areas of the city have become urban heat islands as a result of poor heat exchange, both because of the area's natural geography and from human activity.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The city's numerous cold air corridors, which are slated to remain as free as possible from new construction, therefore play an important role in the urban climate of Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The January average is 3.0 °C (37 °F), while the July average is 18.5 °C (65 °F).
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Precipitation is almost evenly spread throughout the year.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In the 1991–2020 period, the record latest freeze (at 2 m above ground) of spring occurred on 28 April and the record first fall freeze on 13 October.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The geology of Aachen is very structurally heterogeneous.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The oldest occurring rocks in the area surrounding the city originate from the Devonian period and include carboniferous sandstone, greywacke, claystone and limestone.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] These formations are part of the Rhenish Massif, north of the High Fens.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In the Pennsylvanian subperiod of the Carboniferous geological period, these rock layers were narrowed and folded as a result of the Variscan orogeny.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] After this event, and over the course of the following 200 million years, this area has been continuously flattened.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] During the Cretaceous period, the ocean penetrated the continent from the direction of the North Sea up to the mountainous area near Aachen, bringing with it clay, sand, and chalk deposits.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] While the clay (which was the basis for a major pottery industry in nearby Raeren) is mostly found in the lower areas of Aachen, the hills of the Aachen Forest and the Lousberg were formed from upper Cretaceous sand and chalk deposits.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] More recent sedimentation is mainly located in the north and east of Aachen and was formed through Tertiary and Quaternary river and wind activities.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Along the major thrust fault of the Variscan orogeny, there are over 30 thermal springs in Aachen and Burtscheid.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] At the end of 2009, the foreign-born residents of Aachen made up 13.6 percent of the total population.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] A significant portion of foreign residents are students at the RWTH Aachen University.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen is at the western end of the Benrath line that divides High German to the south from the rest of the West Germanic speech area to the north.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen's local dialect is called *Öcher Platt* and belongs to Ripuarian.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The city is divided into seven administrative districts, or boroughs, each with its own district council, district leader, and district authority.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The councils are elected locally by those who live within the district, and these districts are further subdivided into smaller sections for statistical purposes, with each sub-district named by a two-digit number.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The current mayor of Aachen is Michael Ziemons of the CDU, who was elected in 2025.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The Aachen city council governs the city alongside the mayor.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral was erected on the orders of Charlemagne.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Construction began *c.* AD 796, and it was, on completion *c.* 798, the largest cathedral north of the Alps.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] It was modelled after the Basilica of San Vitale, in Ravenna, Italy, and was built by Odo of Metz.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Charlemagne also desired for the chapel to compete with the Lateran Palace, both in quality and authority.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] It was originally built in the Carolingian style, including marble covered walls, and mosaic inlay on the dome.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] On his death, Charlemagne's remains were interred in the cathedral and can be seen there to this day.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The cathedral was extended several times in later ages, turning it into a curious and unique mixture of building styles.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The throne and gallery portion date from the Ottonian, with portions of the original opus sectile floor still visible.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The 13th century saw gables being added to the roof, and after the fire of 1656, the dome was rebuilt.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Finally, a choir was added around the start of the 15th century.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] After Frederick Barbarossa canonised Charlemagne in 1165 the chapel became a destination for pilgrims.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] For 600 years, from 936 to 1531, Aachen Cathedral was the church of coronation for 30 German kings and 12 queens.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The church built by Charlemagne is still the main attraction of the city.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In addition to holding the remains of its founder, it became the burial place of his successor Otto III.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In the upper chamber of the gallery, Charlemagne's marble throne is housed.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral has been designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Most of the marble and columns used in the construction of the cathedral were brought from Rome and Ravenna, including the sarcophagus in which Charlemagne was eventually laid to rest.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] A bronze bear from Gaul was placed inside, along with an equestrian statue from Ravenna, believed to be Theodric, in contrast to a wolf and a statue of Marcus Aurelius in the Capitoline.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Bronze pieces such as the doors and railings, some of which have survived to present day, were cast in a local foundry.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Finally, there is uncertainty surrounding the bronze pine cone in the chapel, and where it was created.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Wherever it was made, it was also a parallel to a piece in Rome, this in Old St.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral Treasury has housed, throughout its history, a collection of liturgical objects.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The origin of this church treasure is in dispute as some say Charlemagne himself endowed his chapel with the original collection, while the rest were collected over time.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Others say all of the objects were collected over time, from such places as Jerusalem and Constantinople.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The location of this treasury has moved over time and was unknown until the 15th century when it was located in the Matthiaskapelle (St.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Matthew's Chapel) until 1873, when it was moved to the Karlskapelle (Charles' Chapel).
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] From there it was moved to the Hungarian Chapel in 1881 and in 1931 to its present location next to the Allerseelenkapelle (Poor Souls' Chapel).
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Only six of the original Carolingian objects have remained, and of those only three are left in Aachen: the Aachen Gospels, a diptych of Christ, and an early Byzantine silk.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The Coronation Gospels and a reliquary burse of St.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Stephen were moved to Vienna in 1798 and the Talisman of Charlemagne was given as a gift in 1804 to Josephine Bonaparte and subsequently to Rheims Cathedral.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] 210 documented pieces have been added to the treasury since its inception, typically to receive in return legitimisation of linkage to the heritage of Charlemagne.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The Lothar Cross, the Gospels of Otto III and multiple additional Byzantine silks were donated by Otto III.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Part of the Pala d'Oro and a covering for the Aachen Gospels were made of gold donated by Henry II.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Frederick Barbarossa donated the candelabrum that adorns the dome and also once "crowned" the Shrine of Charlemagne, which was placed underneath in 1215.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Charles IV donated a pair of reliquaries.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Louis XI gave, in 1475, the crown of Margaret of York, and, in 1481, another arm reliquary of Charlemagne.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Maximilian I and Charles V both gave numerous works of art by Hans von Reutlingen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Continuing the tradition, objects continued to be donated until the present, each indicative of the period of its gifting, with the last documented gift being a chalice from 1960 made by Ewald Mataré.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The Aachen Rathaus, (English: Aachen City Hall or Aachen Town Hall) dated from 1330, lies between two central squares, the *Markt* (marketplace) and the *Katschhof* (between city hall and cathedral).
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The coronation hall is on the first floor of the building.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Inside one can find five frescoes by the Aachen artist Alfred Rethel which show legendary scenes from the life of Charlemagne, as well as Charlemagne's signature.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Also, precious replicas of the Imperial Regalia are kept here.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Since 2009, the city hall has been a station on the *Route Charlemagne*, a tour programme by which historical sights of Aachen are presented to visitors.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] At the city hall, a museum exhibition explains the history and art of the building and gives a sense of the historical coronation banquets that took place there.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] A portrait of Napoleon from 1807 by Louis-André-Gabriel Bouchet and one of his wife Joséphine from 1805 by Robert Lefèvre are viewable as part of the tour.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] As before, the city hall is the seat of the mayor of Aachen and of the city council, and annually the Charlemagne Prize is awarded there.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The *Grashaus*, a late medieval house at the *Fischmarkt*, is one of the oldest non-religious buildings in central Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] It hosted the city archive, and before that, the Grashaus was the city hall until the present building took over this function.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The *Elisenbrunnen* is one of the most famous sights of Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] It is a neo-classical hall covering one of the city's famous fountains.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] It is just a minute away from the cathedral.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Just a few steps in a south-easterly direction lies the 19th-century theatre.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Also of note are two remaining city gates, the *Ponttor* (Pont gate), 800 metres (1⁄2 mile) northwest of the cathedral, and the *Marschiertor* (marching gate), close to the central railway station.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] There are also a few parts of both medieval city walls left, most of them integrated into more recent buildings, but some others still visible.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] There are even five towers left, some of which are used for housing.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Michael's Church, Aachen was built as a church of the Aachen Jesuit Collegium in 1628.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] It is attributed to the Rhine mannerism, and a sample of a local Renaissance architecture.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The rich façade remained unfinished until 1891, when the architect Peter Friedrich Peters added to it.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The church is a Greek Orthodox church today, but the building is used also for concerts because of its good acoustics.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The synagogue in Aachen, which was destroyed on the Night of Broken Glass (Kristallnacht), 9 November 1938, was reinaugurated on 18 May 1995.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] One of the contributors to the reconstructions of the synagogue was Jürgen Linden, the Lord Mayor of Aachen from 1989 to 2009.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] There are numerous other notable churches and monasteries, a few remarkable 17th- and 18th-century buildings in the particular Baroque style typical of the region, a synagogue, a collection of statues and monuments, park areas, cemeteries, among others.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Among the museums in the town are the Suermondt-Ludwig Museum, which has a fine sculpture collection and the Aachen Museum of the International Press, which is dedicated to newspapers from the 16th century to the present.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] The area's industrial history is reflected in dozens of 19th- and early 20th-century manufacturing sites in the city.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Aachen is the administrative centre for the coal-mining industries in neighbouring places to the northeast.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Products manufactured in Aachen include electrical goods, fine woolen textiles, foodstuffs (chocolate and candy), glass, machinery, rubber products, furniture, metal products.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Also in and around Aachen chemicals, plastics, cosmetics, and needles and pins are produced.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Though once a major player in Aachen's economy, today glassware and textile production make up only 10% of total manufacturing jobs in the city.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] There have been a number of spin-offs from the university's IT technology department.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In June 2010, Achim Kampker, together with Günther Schuh, founded a small company to develop electric powered light utility vehicles; in August 2014, it was renamed StreetScooter GmbH.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] This started as a privately organised research initiative at the RWTH Aachen University, before becoming the independent company in Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] Kampker was also the founder and chairman of the European Network for Affordable and Sustainable Electromobility.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In May 2014, the company announced that the city of Aachen, the city council Aachen and the savings bank Aachen had ordered electric vehicles from the company.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In late 2014, approximately 70 employees were manufacturing 200 vehicles annually in the premises of the Waggonfabrik Talbot, the former Talbot/Bombardier plant in Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In December 2014 DHL Group purchased the StreetScooter company from Günther, operating it as a wholly owned subsidiary.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] In 2015, Günther founded a new electric vehicle company, e.GO Mobile, which started producing the e.GO Life electric passenger car and other vehicles in April 2019.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] By April 2016, StreetScooter announced that it would produce 2000 of its electric vans, branded the Work, in Aachen by the end of the year, and would be scaling up to manufacture approximately 10,000 Works annually, starting in 2017, also in Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p01] At the time, this target would make it the largest electric light utility vehicle manufacturer in Europe, surpassing Renault's smaller Kangoo Z.E.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] RWTH Aachen University, established as Polytechnicum in 1870, is one of Germany's Universities of Excellence with strong emphasis on technological research, especially for electrical and mechanical engineering, computer sciences, physics, and chemistry.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The university clinic attached to the RWTH, the Klinikum Aachen, is the biggest single-building hospital in Europe.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Over time, a host of software and computer industries have developed around the university.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] It also maintains a botanical garden (the Botanischer Garten Aachen).
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] FH Aachen, Aachen University of Applied Sciences (AcUAS) was founded in 1971.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The AcUAS offers a classic engineering education in professions such as mechatronics, construction engineering, mechanical engineering or electrical engineering.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] German and international students are educated in more than 20 international or foreign-oriented programmes and can acquire German as well as international degrees (Bachelor/Master) or *Doppelabschlüsse* (double degrees).
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Foreign students account for more than 21% of the student body.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The Katholische Hochschule Nordrhein-Westfalen – Abteilung Aachen (Catholic University of Applied Sciences Northrhine-Westphalia – Aachen department) offers its some 750 students a variety of degree programmes: social work, childhood education, nursing, and co-operative management.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] It also has the only programme of study in Germany especially designed for mothers.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The Hochschule für Musik und Tanz Köln (Cologne University of Music) is one of the world's foremost performing arts schools and one of the largest music institutions for higher education in Europe with one of its three campuses in Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The Aachen campus substantially contributes to the Opera/Musical Theatre master's programme by collaborating with the Theater Aachen and the recently established musical theatre chair through the Rheinische Opernakademie.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The German Army's technical school *(Ausbildungszentrum Technik Landsysteme)* is located in Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The annual CHIO (short for the French term *Concours Hippique International Officiel*) is the biggest equestrian meeting of the world and among horsemen is considered to be as prestigious for equitation as the tournament of Wimbledon for tennis.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Aachen hosted the 2006 FEI World Equestrian Games.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The local football team Alemannia Aachen had a short run in Germany's first division, after its promotion in 2006.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] However, the team could not sustain its status and is now back in the third division.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The stadium "Tivoli", opened in 1928, served as the venue for the team's home games and was well known for its incomparable atmosphere throughout the whole of the second division.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Before the old stadium's demolition in 2011, it was used by amateurs, whilst the Bundesliga Club held its games in the new stadium "Neuer Tivoli" – meaning New Tivoli—a couple of metres down the road.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The building work for the stadium which has a capacity of 32,960, began in May 2008 and was completed by the beginning of 2009.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The Ladies in Black women's volleyball team (part of the "PTSV Aachen" sports club since 2013) has played in the first German volleyball league (DVL) since 2008.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] In June 2022, the local basketball club BG Aachen e.V. was promoted to the 1st regional league.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Aachen's railway station, the Hauptbahnhof (Central Station), was constructed in 1841 for the Cologne–Aachen railway line.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] In 1905, it was moved closer to the city centre.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] It serves main lines to Cologne, Mönchengladbach and Liège as well as branch lines to Heerlen, Alsdorf, Stolberg and Eschweiler.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] ICE high speed trains from Brussels via Cologne to Frankfurt am Main and Eurostar trains from Paris to Cologne also stop at Aachen Central Station.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Four RE lines and two RB lines connect Aachen with the Ruhrgebiet, Mönchengladbach, Spa (Belgium), Düsseldorf and the Siegerland.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The *Euregiobahn*, a regional railway system, reaches several minor cities in the Aachen region.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] There are four smaller stations in Aachen: *Aachen West*, *Aachen Schanz*, *Aachen-Rothe Erde* and *Eilendorf*.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Aachen West has gained in importance with the expansion of RWTH Aachen University.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] There are two stations for intercity bus services in Aachen: Aachen West station, in the north-west of the city, and Aachen Wilmersdorfer Straße, in the north-east.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The first horse tram line in Aachen opened in December 1880.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] After electrification in 1895, it attained a maximum length of 213.5 kilometres (132+5⁄8 miles) in 1915, thus becoming the fourth-longest tram network in Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Many tram lines extended to the surrounding towns of Herzogenrath, Stolberg, Alsdorf as well as the Belgian and Dutch communes of Vaals, Kelmis (then *Altenberg*) and Eupen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The Aachen tram system was linked with the Belgian national interurban tram system.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Like many tram systems in Western Europe, the Aachen tram suffered from poorly maintained infrastructure and was so deemed unnecessary and disrupting for car drivers by local politics.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] On 28 September 1974, the last line 15 (Vaals–Brand) operated for one last day and was then replaced by buses.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] A proposal to reinstate a tram/light rail system under the name *Campusbahn* was dropped after a referendum.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Today, the ASEAG (*Aachener Straßenbahn und Energieversorgungs-AG*, literally "Aachen Tram and Power Supply Company") operates a 1,240.8-kilometre-long (771 mi) bus network with 68 bus routes.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Because of the location at the border, many bus routes extend to Belgium and the Netherlands.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Lines 14 to Eupen, Belgium and 44 to Heerlen, Netherlands are jointly operated with Transport en Commun and Veolia Transport Nederland, respectively.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] ASEAG is one of the main participants in the Aachener Verkehrsverbund (AVV), a tariff association in the region.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Along with ASEAG, city bus routes of Aachen are served by private contractors such as Sadar, Taeter, Schlömer, or DB Regio Bus.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Line 350, which runs from Maastricht, also enters Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Aachen is connected to the Autobahn A4 (west-east), A44 (north-south) and A544 (a smaller motorway from the A4 to the *Europaplatz* near the city centre).
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] There are plans to eliminate traffic jams at the Aachen road interchange.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Maastricht Aachen Airport (IATA: **MST**, ICAO: **EHBK**) is the main airport of Aachen and Maastricht.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] It is located around 15 nautical miles (28 kilometres; 17 miles) northwest of Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] There is a shuttle-service between Aachen and the airport.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] However, the airport only offers limited European destinations.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The nearest major international airports are Cologne Bonn Airport, located 88 km (55 mi) east and Düsseldorf Airport, located 97.1 km (60 mi) northeast of Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Recreational aviation is served by the (formerly military) Aachen Merzbrück Airfield.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Since 1950, a committee of Aachen citizens annually awards the Charlemagne Prize (German: *Karlspreis*) to personalities of outstanding service to the unification of Europe.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] It is traditionally awarded on Ascension Day at the City Hall.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] In 2016, the Charlemagne Award was awarded to Pope Francis.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] In 2004, Pope John Paul II's efforts to unite Europe were honoured with an "Extraordinary Charlemagne Medal", which was awarded for the only time ever.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] Aix is the destination in Robert Browning's poem "How They Brought the Good News from Ghent to Aix", which was published in *Dramatic Romances and Lyrics*, 1845.
[src:achim-großmann/aachen-p02] The poem is a first-person narrative told, in breathless galloping meter, by one of three riders; an urgent midnight errand to deliver "the news which alone could save Aix from her fate".
[src:achim-großmann/aachener-zeitung] The AZ was founded in 1946 as ***Aachener Volkszeitung*** (AVZ) by Jakob Schmitz, Josef Hofmann, Albert Maas and Johannes Ernst, first printed on 22 February 1946.
[src:achim-großmann/aachener-zeitung] It was the first free paper published by Germans after World War II.
[src:achim-großmann/aachener-zeitung] The paper was renamed *Aachener Zeitung* on 6 March 1996.
[src:achim-großmann/aachener-zeitung] The paper was printed initially only two or three times a week, but daily every working day from 1 September 1949; it is sold mainly by subscription and the circulation is about 112,000 copies.
[src:achim-großmann/aachener-zeitung] The paper supplies news from around the world, but with a focus on the region, its politics, economy, culture, sports and weather, for readers in Aachen, Eschweiler, Geilenkirchen and Jülich.
[src:achim-großmann/aachener-zeitung] Bernd Mathieu is the current editor-in-chief, of the Aachener Zeitung from 1995 and of the Aachener Nachrichten from 2003.
[src:achim-großmann/aachener-zeitung] The concept of two newspapers in one *Redaktion* was then new for Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/aachener-zeitung] Mathieu is a lecturer at the Aachen University of Applied Sciences for *Digital Business* in media and communications studies.
[src:achim-großmann/aachener-zeitung] He is a member of the jury of the journalism prize Theodor Wolff Prize.
[src:achim-großmann/aachener-zeitung] Mathieu initiated online news service, namely a digital daily evening news "AmAbend" with photo galleries and videos, provided from 7 pm, in addition to the printed papers which include weekly specials on Wednesdays and Sundays.
[src:achim-großmann/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:achim-großmann/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:achim-großmann/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:achim-großmann/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:achim-großmann/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:achim-großmann/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:achim-großmann/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:achim-großmann/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:achim-großmann/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Alsdorf is located near the border triangle Germany/Belgium/Netherlands in the west of Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Communes bordering Alsdorf are Baesweiler, Aldenhoven, Eschweiler, Würselen, Herzogenrath and Übach-Palenberg.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Alsdorf belongs to the district of Aachen.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Today´s city of Alsdorf is a complex mixture of very different ingredients.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] A part of today's city was a part of the Duchy of Limburg (later united with Duchy of Brabant); and one part belonged to the territory of the Duchy of Jülich.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] In addition, Alsdorf consists of ancient settlements whose history dates back to medieval times, as well as settlements that arose because of the long coal mining tradition in Alsdorf.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] The old settlements are: Alsdorf, Bettendorf, Hoengen, Ofden, Schaufenberg, Warden and Zopp.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] The name Alsdorf was mentioned for the first time in a document of the Catholic Church in the year 1191.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] But it might be much older than 800 years.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] During its history, Alsdorf changed its affiliation a few times.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Along with the duchy of Brabant and the duchy of Limburg, it also belonged to the duchy of Burgundy (1430) and fell to the Habsburgs in 1482.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Then in 1555, it became part of the Spanish Netherlands under the Spanish Habsburgs.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] In 1714, it was returned to the Austrian Habsburgs until the French invasion of 1794.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Pursuant to a judgement of the 1815 Congress of Vienna, Alsdorf was awarded to Prussia.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] With the reconstruction of Germany after the Second World War, Prussia was eliminated, and its western provinces are now the state of North Rhine-Westphalia, where Alsdorf lies.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Until the middle of the 19th century, farming was the main industry.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Only Alsdorf (approximately 1,200) and Hoengen (about 1,400) had more than 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Population in the greater area of today's Alsdorf totalled 4,000 people.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Today the population is more than ten times larger as a result of mining, which came to Alsdorf in the middle of the 19th century.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] The mining industry needed many workers.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] First, it was possible to cover the demand with local workers but as the mine grew, the need for workers grew.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] To be an attractive employer, the mine company built new houses to offer its employees good working conditions.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Between 1860 and 1960, a few bigger and smaller villages were founded.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] These villages are: Begau, Blumenrath, Broicher Siedlung, Busch, Kellersberg, Mariadorf, Neuweiler, Ofden, Ost and Zopp.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] In 1932, the villages Kellerberg, Ofden, Schaufenberg, and Neuweiler were incorporated and the population grew from 11,500 to 19,711.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] The great tragedy on October 21, 1930, demonstrated the danger of mine work.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] In the Anna II Mine, 270 men and one woman were killed.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] It was the second largest mining accident in Germany history.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] The Maria Mine closed in September 1962, and the last mine in Alsdorf shut down in 1992.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Since this time, Alsdorf has successfully changed its image away from a coal city to a modern business location.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] A few business parks have been founded, where a lot of companies have located.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] The current mayor is Tim Krämer (SPD), who was elected with 51.6 % of the votes during the 2025 local elections.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] For over a century, coal mining was the heart of Alsdorf's economy.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Coal production started in 1849, when the Maria Mine opened in Hoengen.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] In 1853, production started in the Anna coal mine of Alsdorf.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] This was the reason for an increase in production and workforce, this was particularly measurable in mine Anna but not in mine Maria, which was closed by September 1962.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Unfortunately, the coal crisis has not spared Alsdorf, and the last mine was closed in 1992.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Alsdorf's biggest employer was the Cinram GmbH, with about 2,000 employees in district of Schaufenberg.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] This company produces up to 2 million DVDs, Blu-rays and CDs daily, exported throughout Europe.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] The company was founded in 1975 by Warner Music and sold in 2003 to the Canadian stock corporation Cinram International.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Customers are well-known record labels and media companies like Warner Music, Twentieth Century Fox and Universal Pictures.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] In 2017 close down its european manufacturing plant at Alsdorf.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Besides acquired companies, which either used the closeness to RWTH Aachen University or which saw the favourable location near the borders to Belgium and the Netherlands as advantage.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] In June 2022 it was announced that in the first quarter of 2023 Continental the German multinational automotive parts manufacturing company would produce fuel tanks at Alsdorf.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] A new factory is built by *Continental Fuel Storage Systems GmbH*.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Alsdorf is located in the heart of Europe, within approximately 200 km of the most important economic centers of the European Union.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] The town lies in the center of the tri-border region of Germany / Netherlands / Belgium.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] The nearest airports are Maastricht Aachen Airport, Cologne Bonn Airport and Düsseldorf Airport.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Alsdorf has a direct connection to Bundesautobahn 4 and Bundesautobahn 44; both are German freeways.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Furthermore, Alsdorf provides a very good bus system.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Every part of Alsdorf or Aachen is served by the buses of ASEAG, the local bus company.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] Since 2005, Alsdorf is connected to the Euregiobahn a regional train system.
[src:achim-großmann/alsdorf] The railway network has extended steadily; hence you can reach Mariadorf since 2011 by regional train.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel was born in Hamburg in West Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Her family moved to East Germany when she was an infant.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] A member of the communist East German Free German Youth (FDJ), Merkel obtained a doctorate in quantum chemistry in 1986 and worked as a research scientist until 1989.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She then entered politics in the wake of the Revolutions of 1989, briefly serving as deputy spokeswoman for the first democratically elected government of East Germany, led by Lothar de Maizière.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Following German reunification in 1990, Merkel was elected to the Bundestag for the state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] As the protégée of Chancellor Helmut Kohl, Merkel was appointed as Minister for Women and Youth in 1991, later becoming Minister for the Environment, Nature Conservation and Nuclear Safety in 1994.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] After the CDU lost the 1998 federal election, Merkel was elected general secretary of the party.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She then became the party's first female leader, and the first female leader of the Opposition, two years later.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Following the 2005 federal election, Merkel was elected chancellor, leading a grand coalition consisting of the CDU, the Christian Social Union (CSU), and the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD).
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She was the first woman to be elected chancellor, and the first chancellor of reunified Germany to have been raised in the former East Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2009 federal election, the CDU obtained the largest share of the vote, and Merkel subsequently formed a coalition government with the Free Democratic Party (FDP), an alliance more favourable to the CDU than the grand coalition.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2013 federal election, the CDU won a landslide victory and formed a second grand coalition with the SPD, after the FDP lost all of its representation in the Bundestag.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2017 federal election, Merkel led the CDU to become the largest party for the fourth time, resulting in the formation of a third grand coalition with the SPD.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In foreign policy, Merkel emphasised international cooperation, both in the context of the EU and NATO, and initiating the Russian reset and strengthening of Eurasian and transatlantic economic relations.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In the first half of 2007, Merkel served as president of the European Council and played a central role in the negotiation of the Treaty of Lisbon and the Berlin Declaration.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's governments managed the 2008 financial crisis and the Euro area crisis.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She negotiated the 2008 European Union stimulus plan, which focused on infrastructure spending and public investment to counteract the Great Recession.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Also in 2008, she actively blocked the access of Ukraine and Georgia in the enlargement of NATO during the 2008 Bucharest summit.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In domestic policy, Merkel's *Energiewende* programme supported the development of renewable energy sources and eventually phased out the use of nuclear power in Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Despite the 2014 Russian annexation of Crimea, which prompted sanctions around the world, she initiated the construction of the controversial Nord Stream 2 pipelines to Russia and protected their construction from United States sanctions imposed in 2019.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Reforms to the *Bundeswehr*, health care reform, the 2010s European migrant crisis, and the COVID-19 pandemic were major issues during her chancellorship.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel stepped down as leader of the CDU in 2018 and did not seek a fifth term as chancellor in the 2021 federal election.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, her legacy came under increased scrutiny both in Germany and abroad for her relatively good relations with Russia and increasing the German economy's dependence on Russia, as well as the downsizing of the *Bundeswehr* that occurred during her tenure.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She has two younger siblings, Marcus Kasner, a physicist, and Irene Kasner, an occupational therapist.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In her childhood and youth, Merkel was known among her peers by the nickname "Kasi", derived from her last name Kasner.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Her paternal grandfather, Ludwik Kasner, was a German policeman of Polish ethnicity.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] After being captured in France during World War I, he joined the Blue Army and likely fought against Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] He married Merkel's grandmother Margarethe, a German from Berlin, and relocated to her hometown where he again worked in the police.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 1930, they Germanised the Polish name Kaźmierczak to Kasner.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's maternal grandparents were the Danzig politician Willi Jentzsch and Gertrud Alma (née Drange), a daughter of the city clerk of Elbing (now Elbląg, Poland) Emil Drange.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Since the mid-1990s, Merkel has publicly mentioned her Polish heritage on several occasions and described herself as a quarter Polish, but her Polish roots became better known as a result of a 2013 biography.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Religion played a key role in the Kasner family's migration from West Germany to East Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's paternal grandfather was originally Catholic but the entire family converted to Lutheranism during the childhood of her father, who later studied Lutheran theology in Heidelberg and Hamburg.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 1954, when Angela was just three months old, her father received a pastorate at the church in Quitzow (a district of Perleberg in Brandenburg), which was then in East Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The family moved to Templin and Merkel grew up in the countryside 90 km (56 mi) north of East Berlin.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 1968, Merkel joined the Free German Youth (FDJ), the official communist youth movement sponsored by the ruling Marxist–Leninist Socialist Unity Party of Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Membership was nominally voluntary, but those who did not join found it difficult to gain admission to higher education.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She did not participate in the secular coming-of-age ceremony Jugendweihe, however, which was common in East Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] During this time, she participated in several compulsory courses on Marxism–Leninism, with her grades only being regarded as "sufficient".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She completed her school education with the best possible average Abitur grade of 1.0.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel continued her education at Karl Marx University, Leipzig, where she studied physics from 1973 to 1978.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] While a student, she participated in the reconstruction of the ruin of the Moritzbastei, a project students initiated to create their own club and recreation facility on campus.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Such an initiative was unprecedented in the GDR of that period, and initially resisted by the university.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] With the backing of the local leadership of the SED party, the project was allowed to proceed.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Near the end of her studies, Merkel sought an assistant professorship at an engineering school.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] As a condition for getting the job, Merkel was told she would need to agree to report on her colleagues to officers of the Stasi.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel declined, using the excuse that she could not keep secrets well enough to be an effective spy.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel worked and studied at the Central Institute for Physical Chemistry of the Academy of Sciences in Berlin-Adlershof from 1978 to 1990.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] At first, she and her husband squatted in Mitte.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] At the Academy of Sciences, she became a member of its FDJ secretariat.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] According to her former colleagues, she openly propagated Marxism as the secretary for "Agitation and Propaganda".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] However, Merkel has denied this claim and stated that she was secretary for culture, which involved activities like obtaining theatre tickets and organising talks by visiting Soviet authors.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] After being awarded a doctorate (*Dr. rer. nat.*) for her thesis on quantum chemistry in 1986, she worked as a researcher and published several academic papers.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 1986, she was allowed to travel to West Germany to attend a congress.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She also participated in a multi-week Russian language course in Donetsk, in the then-Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989 served as the catalyst for Merkel's political career.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Although she did not participate in the crowd celebrations the night the wall came down, one month later Merkel became involved in the growing democracy movement, joining the new party Democratic Awakening (*Demokratischer Aufbruch*, abbreviated to DA).
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Party Leader Wolfgang Schnur appointed her as press spokeswoman of the party in February 1990.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] However, Schnur was revealed to have served as an "informal co-worker" for the Stasi just a few weeks ahead of the first (and only) multi-party election in 1990 and was later expelled from the party.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] As a result, the DA lost most of its electoral support, only managing to obtain four seats in the Volkskammer.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] However, because the DA was a member party of the Alliance for Germany, which won the election in a landslide, the DA was included in the government coalition.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel was appointed deputy spokesperson of this last pre-unification government under Lothar de Maizière.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] De Maizière was impressed with the way Merkel handled journalists investigating Schnur's role in the Stasi.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In April 1990, the DA merged with the East German Christian Democratic Union, which in turn merged with its western counterpart after reunification.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In the German federal election of 1990, the first to be held following reunification, Merkel successfully stood for election to the Bundestag in the parliamentary constituency of Stralsund – Nordvorpommern – Rügen in North Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She received the crucial backing of influential CDU minister and state party chairman Günther Krause.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She was re-elected from this constituency (renamed, with slightly adjusted borders, Vorpommern-Rügen – Vorpommern-Greifswald I in 2003) in every election until the CDU lost its direct mandate from the constituency in the 2021 federal election.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Almost immediately following her entry into parliament, Merkel was appointed by Chancellor Helmut Kohl to serve as Minister for Women and Youth in the federal cabinet.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In November 1991, Merkel, with the support of the federal CDU, ran for the state leadership of the CDU in the state of Brandenburg, which neighbours Berlin.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In June 1993, Merkel was elected leader of the CDU in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, succeeding her former mentor Günther Krause.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Although Merkel had little interest in the political position as such, it has been described as instrumental in building her early political image.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] During her tenure, the government codified the right to preschool education, although the law only went into effect in 1996.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In June 1992, § 218 of the StGB, which governed abortion rights, was rewritten to allow abortions until the 12th week of pregnancy.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Though she was personally opposed to abortion at the time, Merkel abstained during the vote on the bill.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The law was later overturned by the Federal Constitutional Court on the basis that there must be a general prohibition of abortion.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 1994, she was promoted to the position of Minister for the Environment and Nuclear Safety, which gave her greater political visibility and a platform on which to build her personal political career.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] As one of Kohl's protégées and his youngest Cabinet Minister, she was frequently referred to by Kohl as "my girl" (*mein Mädchen*).
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] During this period, she was closely mentored by Kohl.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] As Minister of the Environment, Merkel was instrumental in setting up the United Nations 1995 Berlin Climate Change Conference.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She is often credited as having brought about its most notable result, the first international commitment to a reduction of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Around this time, she also first hired Beate Baumann, who would remain a close advisor to Merkel.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's performance as Minister of the Environment was criticised as "pitiful" by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] After the Kohl Government was defeated at the 1998 election, Merkel was appointed Secretary-General of the CDU.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The 1998 election had widespread impacts; it was the CDU's worst performance in a federal election since 1949, and it resulted in Germany's first post-war left-wing government, led by the SPD.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In the wake of this defeat on the federal level, Merkel oversaw a string of CDU election victories in six out of seven state elections in 1999, breaking the long-standing SPD-Green hold on the Bundesrat.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Following a party funding scandal that compromised many leading figures of the CDU – including Kohl himself and his successor as CDU Leader, Wolfgang Schäuble – Merkel criticised her former mentor publicly and advocated a fresh start for the party without him.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] On 10 April 2000, Merkel was elected to replace Schäuble as Chairperson of the CDU, becoming the first female leader of a German party.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Following Merkel's election as CDU Leader, the CDU did not obtain electoral victories in subsequent state elections.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In February 2001, her rival Friedrich Merz voiced his intention to become Gerhard Schröder's main challenger for Chancellorship in the 2002 election.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's ambition to become Chancellor was well-known, but she lacked the support of the most influential members within her own party.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Rival candidate and leader of the CSU Edmund Stoiber was much more popular within the party at the time.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In a private negotiation that came to be known as the Wolfratshausen Breakfast, Merkel agreed to cede the opportunity to challenge Schröder to Stoiber; in exchange, she was to become leader of the CDU/CSU faction in the Bundestag following the election.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Although pre-election polling had indicated that voters strongly favoured Stoiber, he went on to lose the election by a thin margin.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The election campaign was dominated by the Iraq War.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] While Chancellor Schröder had made clear he would not join the war in Iraq, Merkel was in support of the war at the time, although she later claimed that she had opposed it.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] After Stoiber's defeat in 2002, in addition to her role as CDU Leader, Merkel became Leader of the Opposition in the Bundestag, as had been agreed upon between her and Stoiber.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Friedrich Merz, who had held the post prior to the 2002 election, was eased out to make way for Merkel.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel supported a substantial reform agenda for Germany's economic and social system and was considered more pro-market than her own party (the CDU).
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She advocated German labour law changes, specifically removing barriers to laying off employees and increasing the allowed number of work hours in a week.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She argued that existing laws made the country less competitive, because companies could not easily control labour costs when business was slow.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel argued that Germany should phase out nuclear power less quickly than the Schröder administration had planned.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel advocated a strong transatlantic partnership and German-American friendship.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In the spring of 2003, defying strong public opposition, Merkel came out in favour of the 2003 invasion of Iraq, describing it as "unavoidable".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She also criticised the government's support for the accession of Turkey to the European Union, instead arguing in favour of a "privileged partnership".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] On 30 May 2005, Merkel won the CDU/CSU nomination to challenge Chancellor Gerhard Schröder of the SPD in the 2005 federal elections.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Her party began the campaign with a 21–point lead over the SPD in national opinion polls, although her personal popularity lagged behind that of the incumbent.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] However, the CDU/CSU campaign suffered when Merkel, having made economic competence central to the CDU's platform, confused gross and net income twice during a televised debate.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She regained some momentum after she announced that she would appoint Paul Kirchhof, a former judge at the German Constitutional Court and leading fiscal policy expert, as Minister of Finance.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel and the CDU lost ground after Kirchhof proposed the introduction of a flat tax in Germany, again undermining the party's broad appeal on economic affairs.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] This was compounded by Merkel's proposal to increase VAT to reduce Germany's deficit and fill the gap in revenue from a flat tax.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The SPD were able to increase their support simply by pledging not to introduce flat taxes or increase VAT.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Although Merkel's standing recovered after she distanced herself from Kirchhof's proposals, she remained considerably less popular than Schröder, who had been perceived as the more generally competent and trustworthy candidate.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The CDU's lead was down to 9 percentage points on the eve of the election, with Merkel having a significant lead in popularity based on opinion polls.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] On 18 September 2005, Merkel's CDU/CSU and Schröder's SPD went head-to-head in the national elections, with the CDU/CSU winning 35.2% (CDU 27.8% / CSU 7.5%) of the second votes to the SPD's 34.2%.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The result was so close that both Schröder and Merkel initially claimed victory.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Neither the SPD–Green coalition nor the CDU/CSU and its preferred coalition partners, the Free Democratic Party, held enough seats to form a majority in the Bundestag.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] A grand coalition between the CDU/CSU and SPD would face the challenge of both parties demanding the chancellorship.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] However, after three weeks of negotiations, the two parties reached a deal for a grand coalition whereby Merkel would become Chancellor and the SPD would hold 8 of the 16 seats in the cabinet.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The deal was approved by both parties at party conferences on 14 November 2005.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel was elected Chancellor by the majority of delegates (397 to 217) in the newly assembled Bundestag on 22 November 2005, but 51 members of the governing coalition voted against her.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Reports at the time indicated that the grand coalition would pursue a mix of policies, some of which differed from Merkel's political platform as leader of the opposition and candidate for Chancellor.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The coalition's intent was to cut public spending whilst increasing VAT (from 16 to 19%), social insurance contributions and the top rate of income tax.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] When announcing the coalition agreement, Merkel stated that the main aim of her government would be to reduce unemployment, and that it was this issue on which her government would be judged.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Reform of the German healthcare system was a salient issue during the 2005 election; the previous system had been criticised as inefficient and overly bureaucratic.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] After a significant period of negotiations, a deal was passed in 2006.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] While this agreement was described as having "saved the coalition government", it was also widely criticised as ineffectual.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The deal also increased the tax burden on employers and their publicly insured employees.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The 2006 round of reforms introduced the "health insurance duty", which establishes that individuals must be insured either through the public insurance system or through private insurance firms and accordingly cannot be uninsured.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The reforms also targeted preventive healthcare as a priority, particularly with regards to eldercare.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] On 4 October 2008, following the Irish Government's decision to guarantee all deposits in private savings accounts, a move she had strongly criticised, Merkel said there were no plans for the German Government to do the same.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The following day, Merkel stated that the government would guarantee private savings account deposits, after all.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] However, two days later, on 6 October 2008, it emerged that the pledge was simply a political move that would not be backed by legislation.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Most other European governments eventually either raised the limits or promised to guarantee savings in full.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The German government stepped in to assist the mortgage company Hypo Real Estate with a bailout.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The deal was agreed upon on 6 October, with German banks contributing €30 billion and the Bundesbank €20 billion to an emergency credit line.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] At the time of the Greek government-debt crisis, Germany was the largest creditor of the Greek government, giving it significant negotiating power.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel is often credited as having "saved the Euro", primarily due to her coordinating role in the development of debt relief policy.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The austerity measures imposed on debtors such as Greece, which were a significant part of Merkel's position in the negotiations, have been criticised as overly harsh by some observers.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Critics also highlighted Germany's own debt management issues.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In the course of the 2008 financial crisis, the Merkel cabinet increased the budget of the Kurzarbeit programme significantly and extended the permitted duration of such contracts from 6 months to 18 months.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Although similar provisions had existed previously, the Merkel cabinet's expansion of the programme was widely praised and is credited with having saved 500,000 jobs during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's CDU was re-elected in 2009 with an increased number of seats and could form a governing coalition with the FDP.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] After brief negotiations, the second Merkel cabinet was sworn in on 28 October 2009.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In early 2011, Merkel's approval ratings plummeted, resulting in heavy losses in state elections for her party.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] An August 2011 poll found her coalition had only 36% support compared to a rival potential coalition's 51%.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Notwithstanding the effects of the 2008 financial crisis, unemployment sank below 3 million unemployed people in 2011.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Following increased debate on the subject in the summer of 2010, the German government announced plans to abolish conscription in Germany, making the *Bundeswehr* a volunteer military, in November 2010.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The decision was finalised in December that year, and conscription was suspended on 1 July 2011.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Although somewhat popular at the time, the decision has later come under scrutiny, particularly following to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] It has also been criticised in conjunction with Germany's financial commitments to NATO.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 2023, 61% of Germans said that they were in favour of reestablishing conscription.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Responding to a budget deficit of €11 billion in the public healthcare system in 2009, the Merkel government passed widely unpopular healthcare reforms in 2010.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The changes reduced healthcare spending in certain areas and increased employer and employee contributions to 15.5% of gross wages.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The reforms also established that future contribution increases would only affect the contributions by employers, which was criticised by opposition parties and trade unions.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In the election of September 2013, Merkel won one of the most decisive victories in German history, achieving the best result for the CDU/CSU since reunification and coming within five seats of the first absolute majority in the Bundestag since 1957.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] However, their preferred coalition partner, the FDP, failed to enter parliament for the first time since 1949, being below the minimum of 5% of second votes required to enter parliament.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The CDU/CSU turned to the SPD to form the third grand coalition in postwar German history and the second under Merkel's leadership.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The third Cabinet of Angela Merkel was sworn in on 17 December 2013.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel scored well in opinion polls on her handling of the recent euro crisis (69% rated her performance as good rather than poor), and her approval rating reached an all-time high of 77% in February 2012 and again in July 2014.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Throughout the course of the European migrant crisis, Merkel encouraged cooperation between EU member states, urging that Europe needs to act "as a whole".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In late August 2015, at the height of the crisis, Merkel's government suspended the Dublin Regulation, which stipulated that asylum seekers must seek asylum in the first EU country they arrive in.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel announced that Germany would also process asylum applications from Syrian refugees if they had come to Germany through other EU countries.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] That year, nearly 1.1 million asylum seekers entered Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel coined the phrase *Wir schaffen das* (literally 'We can do this') around this time.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Junior coalition partner and Vice Chancellor Sigmar Gabriel said that Germany could take in 500,000 refugees annually for the next several years.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] German opposition to the government's admission of the new wave of migrants was strong and coupled with a rise in anti-immigration protests.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel insisted that Germany had the economic strength to cope with the influx of migrants and reiterated that there is no legal maximum limit on the number of migrants Germany can take.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In September 2015, enthusiastic crowds across the country welcomed arriving refugees and migrants.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Horst Seehofer, leader of the Christian Social Union in Bavaria (CSU)—the sister party of Merkel's Christian Democratic Union—and then-Bavarian Minister President, attacked Merkel's policies.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] He argued for a punitive reduction in EU funding for member countries that rejected mandatory refugee quotas.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Meanwhile, Yasmin Fahimi, secretary-general of the Social Democratic Party (SPD), the junior partner of the ruling coalition, praised Merkel's policy allowing migrants in Hungary to enter Germany as "a strong signal of humanity to show that Europe's values are valid also in difficult times".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's approval rating dropped to 54% in October 2015, the lowest it had been since 2011.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In November 2015, there were talks inside the governing coalition to stop family unification for migrants for two years and to establish "Transit Zones" on the border.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Additionally, there were plans to provide housing to migrants with a low likelihood of getting approved for asylum until the processing of their application.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] This led to increased tensions between the CSU, who were generally in favour of these measures and threatened to leave the coalition without them, and the SPD, who opposed them; Merkel agreed to the measures.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The November 2015 Paris attacks prompted a reevaluation of the German government's stance on EU migration policy.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] While she did not directly limit the number of immigrants, Merkel tightened asylum policy in Germany, for example through more thorough vetting of migrants with respect to internal safety and security.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In August 2016, following the Würzburg train attack in Germany and various other Islamist terror attacks in Europe, Merkel's approval rating dropped to 47%.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Half of Germans did not want her to serve a fourth term in office, with only 42% in favour of another term in office.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In a poll from October that year, her approval rating was found to have risen again; 54% of Germans were found to be satisfied with the work of Merkel as Chancellor.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] According to another poll taken in November 2016, 59% were to found to be in favour of a renewed Chancellorship candidature in 2017.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] According to a poll carried out shortly after the 2016 Berlin truck attack, 56% of Germans named Merkel as a political leader they trusted to solve their country's problems.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In October 2016, Merkel travelled to Mali and Niger.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The diplomatic visit took place to discuss how their governments could improve conditions which caused people to flee those countries and how illegal migration through and from these countries could be reduced.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The migrant crisis spurred right-wing electoral preferences across Germany with the Alternative for Germany (AfD) gaining 12% of the vote in the 2017 German federal election.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] These developments prompted debates over the reasons for increased right-wing populism in Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Some researchers have argued that increased right-wing preferences are a result of the European migrant crisis, particularly the increasingly common perception that refugees constitute an ethnic and cultural threat to Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Some observers have described Merkel's policymaking with respect to the migrant crisis as a success.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 2022, the United Nations' High Commissioner for Refugees granted Merkel the Nansen Award for her "courage and compassion" during the crisis.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] However, Merkel has also faced significant criticism, particularly with regards to her policymaking early in the crisis, which some critics describe as hypocritically unilateral.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2017 federal election, Merkel led her party to victory for the fourth time.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] However, both the CDU/CSU and the SPD received a significantly lower proportion of the vote than they did in 2013, and the CDU/CSU subsequently attempted to form a coalition with the FDP and Greens.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The SPD announced that they would go into the Opposition, both due to their loss of popular support and because the idea of another grand coalition was widely unpopular at the time.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The FDP eventually withdrew from negotiations with the CDU/CSU, leading to a stalemate.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The German President Frank-Walter Steinmeier subsequently appealed successfully to the SPD to change their hard stance against coalition with the CDU/CSU, and the SPD agreed to a third grand coalition with the CDU/CSU.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The negotiations leading up to this agreement were the longest in German post-war history, lasting almost six months.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] A YouGov survey published in late December 2017 found that just 36% of all respondents wanted Merkel to stay at the helm until 2021, while half of those surveyed voters called for a change at the top before the end of the legislature.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The Fourth Merkel cabinet was sworn in on 14 March 2018.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] As part of the newly formed government, the CSU's Horst Seehofer took over the role of Interior Minister.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Seehofer announced that he had a "master plan for faster asylum procedures, and more consistent deportations." Under Seehofer's plan, Germany would immediately reject prospective immigrants who had already been deported or were subject to an entry ban.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Additionally, the police would be instructed to turn away all applicants who had previously registered elsewhere in the EU, no matter if these countries agreed to take them back.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel feared that unilaterally sending migrants back to neighbouring countries without seeking a multilateral European agreement could endanger the stability of the European Union.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In June 2018, Seehofer issued an ultimatum to Merkel; as Interior Minister, he could unilaterally implement the policy without her support.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Although he eventually agreed to cooperate with Merkel while she negotiated with other EU member countries, he went on to reject the EU agreement that she obtained.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] On 1 July 2018, during a meeting with party leadership, Seehofer declared his intention to resign from his position in protest.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] During the night of 2 July 2018, Seehofer and Merkel announced they had settled their differences and agreed to instead accept a compromise of tighter border control.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] As a result of the agreement, Seehofer agreed to not resign, and to negotiate bilateral agreements with the specific countries himself.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Seehofer received some criticism for his stance in the crisis.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In the initial phases of the pandemic, Germany established a crisis team to manage Germany's containment policy and pandemic response.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In late February 2020, referring to this crisis team, Merkel recommended an approach characterised by moderation and an avoidance of extreme or universal measures (*Maß und Mitte*).
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The speech was well-received both nationally and internationally, receiving widespread attention and an award for "speech of the year".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] On 6 April 2020, Merkel stated: "In my view ... the European Union is facing the biggest test since its foundation and member states must show greater solidarity so that the bloc can emerge stronger from the economic crisis unleashed by the pandemic".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel has won international plaudits for her handling of the pandemic in Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Later that month, Merkel was praised for her accessible explanation of the basic reproduction number, which had been an important metric in the German government's pandemic response.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel opposed mandatory vaccinations, instead stressing scientific literacy and education.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] During the German presidency of the European Council, Merkel spearheaded negotiations for the Next Generation EU reconstruction package.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] On 29 October 2018, Merkel announced that she would not seek reelection as leader of CDU at their party conference in December 2018, but intended to remain as chancellor until the 2021 German federal election was held.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She stated that she did not plan to seek any political office after this.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The resignations followed October setbacks for the CSU in the Bavarian state election and for the CDU in the Hessian state election.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In August 2019, Merkel hinted that she might return to academia at the end of her term in 2021.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She decided not to suggest any person as her successor as leader of the CDU.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] However, political observers had long considered Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer as Merkel's protégé groomed for succession.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] This view was confirmed when Kramp-Karrenbauer – widely seen as the chancellor's favourite for the post – was voted to succeed Merkel as leader of the CDU in December 2018.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Kramp-Karrenbauer's elevation to Defence Minister after Ursula von der Leyen's departure to become president of the European Commission also boosted her standing as Merkel's most likely candidate for succession.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 2019, media outlets speculated that Kramp-Karrenbauer might take over Merkel's position as Chancellor sooner than planned if the current governing coalition proved unsustainable.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The possibility was neither confirmed nor denied by the party.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In February 2020, Kramp-Karrenbauer announced that she would resign as party leader of the CDU in the summer, after party members in Thuringia defied official party lines and voted with Alternative for Germany to support an FDP candidate for minister-president.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Kramp-Karrenbauer was succeeded by Armin Laschet at the 2021 CDU leadership election.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2021 federal election, the SPD won the most votes.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] This necessitated long negotiations among the various parties to form a government.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] On 23 November 2021, a new coalition was announced, with Olaf Scholz nominated to succeed Merkel.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel continued to serve as chancellor until 8 December 2021, when Scholz was sworn in.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The constituency she had held since its establishment in the German reunification was won by Anna Kassautzki (SPD).
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] On 31 January 2022, less than two months after she left office, her long-time rival Friedrich Merz, whom she beat in 2002 to become leader of the opposition, took over as leader of the CDU.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In April that year, a spokesperson for Merkel stated that she "stood by her position at the NATO summit in Bucharest in 2008", when she had opposed Ukraine's membership in the North Atlantic Alliance, a decision that had come under increased scrutiny.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] On 1 June 2022, Merkel made her first semi-public comments about political affairs since leaving office, at a retirement party for Reiner Hoffmann, the president of the German Trade Union Confederation.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] On 7 June 2022, Merkel made her first public comments.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She also said that by the end of her chancellorship in September 2021, it had been clear that Putin was moving in the direction of conflict and that he was finished with the Normandy Format talks.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Following her retirement, Merkel wrote a memoir called *Freedom* (Freiheit), with her longtime assistant and adviser, Beate Baumann.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] It was released on 26 November 2024 with the title *Freedom: Memories 1954–2021*.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The book was published in 30 languages and consists of 736 pages.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In January 2025, Merkel criticised Friedrich Merz for introducing a non-binding resolution supporting restrictions on immigration that passed in the Bundestag with the help of the AfD.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Following the CDU/CSU's victory in the 2025 German federal election, Merkel attended the first round of voting in the Bundestag to elect Merz as Chancellor on 6 May 2025.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In October 2025 Merkel gave a long interview to Hungarian media in which she made a number of controversial statements, partly reverting her previous position.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She said that in 2021 she attempted to build a "new diplomatic format" to speak to Putin "as EU", but this was "opposed by Poland and Baltic states" and then she left her position shortly before the war broke out in 2022, thus indirectly blaming the countries for the war.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She also said that "coronavirus pandemic that played a decisive role in Russia’s invasion of Ukraine" because Putin was afraid of the virus and didn't want to talk face to face.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Anyone who doesn't accept that is in the wrong place here." She continued to say that immigrants should integrate and adopt Germany's culture and values.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] This added to a growing debate within Germany on the acceptable levels and mechanisms of immigration, its effects on Germany, and the degree to which Muslim immigrants had integrated into German society.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel is in favour of a "mandatory solidarity mechanism" for relocation of asylum-seekers from Italy and Greece to other EU member states as part of the long-term solution to Europe's migrant crisis.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's foreign policy has focused on strengthening European cooperation and international trade agreements.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She and her governments have been closely associated with the change through trade (*Wandel durch Handel*) policy.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] For this, she has come under criticism, especially after the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel has been widely described as the *de facto* leader of the European Union throughout her tenure as Chancellor.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 2015, with the absence of Stephen Harper, Merkel became the only leader to have attended every G20 meeting since the first in 2008, having been present at a record fifteen summits as of 2021.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She hosted the twelfth meeting at the 2017 G20 Hamburg summit.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel favors the Association Agreement between Ukraine and the European Union.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In December 2012, she stated that its implementation depends on reforms in Ukraine.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel expressed support for Israel's right to self-defence in the context of the 2014 Israel–Gaza conflict.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She telephoned Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on 9 July to condemn "without reservation rocket fire on Israel".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] On 20 June 2018, which was World Refugee Day, Merkel said that there had been "no moral or political justification" for the post-war expulsion of ethnic Germans from Central and Eastern European countries.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] At the World Economic Forum in Davos, 2013, Merkel said that Europe had only 7% of the global population and produced only 25% of the global GDP, but that it accounted for almost 50% of global social expenditure.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] She went on to say that Europe could only maintain its prosperity by being innovative and measuring itself against the best.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] After this, the comparison became a central element in major speeches.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The *Financial Times* commented: "Although Ms Merkel stopped short of suggesting that a ceiling on social spending might be one yardstick for measuring competitiveness, she hinted as much in the light of soaring social spending in the face of an ageing population.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel has been credited as a key part of 2007 G8 negotiations that led to a significantly more ambitious renewable energy transition commitment than had been anticipated.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In September 2010, the coalition government published a long-term plan for sustainable development of the electrical grid until 2050; efforts to transition to sustainable and otherwise preferable sources of energy have been termed Energy Transition (*Energiewende*).
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Although the initial plan was criticised for lifetime extensions of nuclear power plants, it was amended following the Fukushima nuclear disaster, and the last nuclear power plants in Germany were shut down in April 2023.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The plan also aimed at a 40% reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by 2020, a goal that was initially achieved largely due to reductions in demand during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] However, emissions increased to a level above the target in 2022.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In preparation for the 2015 Paris Climate Change Conference, Merkel announced that Germany would significantly increase its contributions to international climate aid and financing by 2020.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 2016, some observers criticised Merkel's lack of action with regards to climate change that year.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 2017, Merkel criticised the Trump administration's decision to withdraw from the 2015 Paris Agreement and reaffirmed the commitment of the remaining G20 members to the treaty.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In early 2019, a governmental commission appointed by the coalition government approved a plan to phase out coal power plants by 2038, allocating a budget of €40 billion to the plan.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In September 2019, the Merkel government announced a set of climate change mitigation policies with a total budget of €54 billion.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Although described as a "new beginning for Germany's climate policy" by then-minister of the environment Svenja Schulze, the package was widely criticised; environmental protection groups have labelled it insufficient, and opposition parties have argued that it is ineffective.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] Prominent climate scientists have called it "a failure of the political system" and "ridiculous".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 2009, Merkel announced plans to take on additional government debt in order to stimulate economic growth, arguing that this should take priority over other fiscal concerns.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] The Merkel government's tax policy at the time was widely criticised, mostly for taking on additional debt instead of increasing tax rates at high levels of income.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 2010, Merkel expressed support for a global financial transaction tax, but was ultimately unsuccessful in international negotiations on the matter.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p01] In 2019, Merkel argued for the importance of a balanced government budget, rejecting calls for additional investment to stimulate growth.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's chancellorship attracted criticism across several policy areas, including her handling of Islam and public integration debates, the eurozone crisis, migration, Turkey, China, Russia, energy policy and the wider development of Euroscepticism in Europe.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was criticised for attending the 2010 M100 Media Award ceremony at which Danish cartoonist Kurt Westergaard was honoured.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Westergaard had drawn cartoons central to the Jyllands-Posten Muhammad cartoons controversy.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Although Merkel defended her attendance as a statement in favour of press freedom, critics argued that her presence gave political legitimacy to material widely viewed by Muslims as offensive.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] The Central Council of Muslims in Germany criticised the decision, saying that Westergaard had insulted the Prophet Muhammad and that the award came at a highly charged time in Germany's debate over Islam and immigration.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Politicians from Die Linke and the Greens also criticised Merkel's participation, while commentators noted the sensitivity of a German chancellor and leader of the Christian Democratic Union personally honouring the cartoonist during a period of intense debate over Muslim integration.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was also criticised from within her own political camp after stating in 2015 that "Islam is part of Germany", a formulation previously associated with former German president Christian Wulff.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Volker Kauder, then parliamentary group leader of the CDU/CSU, rejected the statement, saying that Muslims belonged to Germany but Islam did not.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Several of Merkel's public formulations became targets of criticism and ridicule.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Her frequent use of the term *alternativlos* to describe measures taken during the European sovereign-debt crisis was criticised as politically undemocratic, since it implied that alternatives to her policies were unnecessary or illegitimate.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] The term was named Germany's Un-word of the Year in 2010.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Her 2013 statement that the internet was *Neuland* also prompted widespread online mockery and criticism.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's handling of the European sovereign-debt crisis was one of the most criticised aspects of her chancellorship.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that her government turned the eurozone crisis into a test of fiscal discipline and debtor-country compliance, rather than treating it as a structural crisis of the monetary union.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Commentators and politicians in several EU member states accused Berlin of imposing excessive austerity on countries such as Greece, Spain and Portugal, deepening social hardship and fuelling anti-EU sentiment.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel also faced criticism from within her own political tradition.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] In July 2011, *Der Spiegel* reported that former chancellor Helmut Kohl, Merkel's former mentor and a central figure in German reunification and European integration, had criticised her handling of the eurozone crisis.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] The criticism intensified during the 2015 Greek bailout negotiations, after the election of the Syriza-led government in January 2015.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel and the German government were identified with the creditor side's insistence on prior reforms, fiscal consolidation, conditionality and privatisation before the release of further funds.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] In July 2015, after Greece missed a repayment to the International Monetary Fund, its second bailout expired and Greek voters rejected the creditors' proposal in a referendum, Merkel and other eurozone leaders pressed Greece to accept a third bailout under stricter terms.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Critics accused Merkel and finance minister Wolfgang Schäuble of using the threat of *Grexit* as leverage and of forcing Greece to surrender fiscal and economic sovereignty in order to remain in the eurozone.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Criticism also focused on the requirement for Greece to privatise or transfer control of state assets.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Opponents argued that the bailout framework went beyond fiscal adjustment by requiring the disposal of strategic Greek public assets, thereby weakening Greek economic sovereignty.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] The 14 Greek regional airports concession became one of the most symbolic examples.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] A preliminary deal with a consortium led by Germany's Fraport AG had been agreed in 2014, but was reviewed after the Syriza government came to power.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] In August 2015, shortly after the third bailout agreement, Greece confirmed that it would proceed with the concession as part of the latest bailout with its lenders.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] The agreement was signed in December 2015 and Fraport Greece began operating the airports in April 2017 under a long-term concession.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] For critics in Greece and southern Europe, the Fraport concession became emblematic of a wider creditor-driven programme in which public assets were transferred to foreign operators while Greek society absorbed the costs of austerity.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] The same criticism was applied to other privatisations, including the sale of a majority stake in the Port of Piraeus to China's COSCO, the sale of railway operator TRAINOSE to Italy's Ferrovie dello Stato Italiane and the sale of a further stake in OTE to Germany's Deutsche Telekom.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Scholars and commentators have linked the eurozone crisis and the subsequent austerity policies to the rise of Euroscepticism and radical parties across Europe.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] In this criticism, Merkel's crisis management is presented not only as an economic policy failure, but also as a political factor that weakened trust in EU institutions and mainstream parties in several member states.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's response to the European migrant crisis of 2015 was heavily criticised by opponents in Germany and abroad.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that the size and speed of the inflow exposed weaknesses in Germany's administrative capacity and contributed to a public backlash against Merkel's government.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Analysts have linked this backlash to the rise of the Alternative for Germany and to broader changes in the German party system.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's refugee policy also became a recurring target in far-right and Eurosceptic discourse, where it was portrayed as evidence of elite detachment from public concerns over borders, identity and security.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] More broadly, the eurozone crisis and the refugee crisis have been identified in academic literature as key drivers of rising Euroscepticism and support for radical parties across Europe in the 2010s.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Critics of Merkel argue that her role in both crises made her one of the central political figures associated with this wider backlash.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was criticised for her pragmatic relationship with Turkish president Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, particularly after the 2015 refugee crisis.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that her reliance on Turkey to reduce irregular migration into the European Union gave Erdoğan political leverage over Germany and the EU at a time when his government was facing increasing criticism over human rights, press freedom and the rule of law.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Opponents argued that the arrangement prioritised border control over refugee protection and made the EU dependent on cooperation with an increasingly authoritarian Turkish government.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel faced further criticism during the Böhmermann affair in April 2016, when her government allowed prosecutors to consider a case against German comedian Jan Böhmermann after Erdoğan complained about a satirical poem.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Critics accused Merkel of failing to defend freedom of expression and of accommodating Erdoğan.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] A Reuters-reported poll found that two thirds of Germans opposed her decision to allow the prosecution to proceed.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was also criticised over Germany's approach to Turkish pressure on Greece and Cyprus.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] During the 2020 Greek–Turkish border crisis, Erdoğan opened Turkey's border with Europe and thousands of migrants attempted to enter Greece.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel criticised Erdoğan for using refugees to express political grievances with the EU, but critics argued that Germany's wider policy remained constrained by its dependence on Turkish cooperation.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Similar criticism arose during the Eastern Mediterranean crisis, when Turkey carried out energy exploration and maritime claims disputed by Greece and Cyprus.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that Germany under Merkel prioritised mediation and de-escalation over firm solidarity with Greece and Cyprus.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Academic analysis of the crisis noted that Germany avoided full identification with the positions of Cyprus and Greece, objected to a sanctions-based agenda against Turkey and sought to maintain open diplomatic channels with Ankara.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was criticised for failing to take a tougher line towards the People's Republic of China.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that her governments prioritised German commercial interests and export access over stronger public criticism of Beijing on human rights, Hong Kong and strategic dependency.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Her approach was frequently characterised by opponents as overly cautious and too focused on trade.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] The criticism intensified during the Hong Kong protests and wider European debates over relations with China.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's China policy was criticised as an example of Germany's reluctance to confront authoritarian governments when major economic interests were involved.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Some commentators later described China as one of the major weaknesses of her foreign-policy legacy.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Merkel faced renewed criticism over her Russia policy.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that she had underestimated Vladimir Putin's ambitions, relied too heavily on diplomacy and détente, and failed to prepare Germany and Europe for a more confrontational Russian policy.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Her governments were criticised for allowing Germany to become heavily dependent on Russian energy, including through Nord Stream 1 and Nord Stream 2.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was also criticised over the condition of the Bundeswehr during and after her chancellorship.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that Germany's armed forces had been neglected, underfunded and left poorly prepared despite growing security risks in Europe.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] This criticism became more prominent after the invasion of Ukraine, when Germany's defence policy came under closer domestic and international scrutiny.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's broader approach to Russia was associated with *Wandel durch Handel*, the policy of pursuing close economic ties with authoritarian governments in the expectation that trade would encourage moderation or democratisation.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] After Russia's invasion of Ukraine, this policy came under intense criticism, with Merkel receiving much of the blame for Germany's strategic dependency on Moscow.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy also criticised Merkel and former French president Nicolas Sarkozy for blocking Ukraine's NATO aspirations in 2008.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel defended the decision, arguing that Ukraine would have been militarily weaker had the conflict escalated earlier.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's energy policy was criticised for combining the phase-out of nuclear power with continued dependence on fossil fuel imports, including Russian gas.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that the nuclear phase-out reduced reliable domestic low-carbon power generation and increased Germany's exposure to imported energy.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] The criticism became stronger during the 2021–2022 global energy crisis, when rising energy prices and supply concerns placed Germany's energy strategy under scrutiny.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Opponents also criticised the interaction between Germany's nuclear exit, coal phase-out and climate policy.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] While Merkel's governments supported the European Green Deal and long-term decarbonisation, critics argued that the transition was poorly sequenced and left Germany vulnerable to both energy insecurity and high prices.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was criticised in debates over the wider direction of the European Union.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Some politicians and commentators argued that German-led austerity during the eurozone crisis, the handling of the migration crisis and the reluctance of EU leaders to accommodate British concerns contributed to anti-EU sentiment.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] In debates over Brexit, critics claimed that continental Europe, including Germany under Merkel, bore part of the responsibility for the political climate that led to the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] This argument was particularly common among Eurosceptic and right-wing critics, who linked the eurozone and migration crises to declining trust in EU institutions.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Studies of far-right discourse in Germany have noted that AfD politicians sometimes portrayed Merkel's refugee policy as contributing to Brexit.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Scholars generally treat Brexit as the result of multiple domestic and European factors, but critics of Merkel have continued to cite it as part of a broader backlash against the EU during her period of leadership.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was widely described as the *de facto* leader of the European Union throughout her tenure as Chancellor.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] She was named the world's second most powerful person by *Forbes* magazine in 2012 and 2015, following Barack Obama and Vladimir Putin respectively, the highest ranking ever achieved by a woman.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] On 26 March 2014, Merkel became the longest-serving incumbent head of government in the European Union.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] In December 2015, Merkel was named as *Time* magazine's Person of the Year, with the magazine's cover declaring her to be the "Chancellor of the Free World".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] In 2018, Merkel was named the most powerful woman in the world for a record fourteenth time by *Forbes*.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Following the election of Donald Trump to the US presidency in 2016, Merkel was described by *The New York Times* as "the Liberal West's Last Defender", and as the "leader of the free world" by a number of commentators, including Hillary Clinton.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] In a 2018 survey, Merkel was found to be the most widely respected world leader.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] *The Atlantic* described her in 2019 as "the world's most successful living politician, on the basis of both achievement and longevity".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Harvard University President Larry Bacow described her as "one of the most widely admired and broadly influential statespeople of our time".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Critics have argued that Merkel's policymaking during the 2015 migrant crisis has damaged the integrity of the EU.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Some have also commented that Germany's failure to meet financial commitments to NATO, Merkel's blocking of the accession of Ukraine to NATO in 2008, and the abolishment of conscription have together weakened the positions of Germany and Europe following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel has been described as having significantly shaped the political landscape of Germany, particularly the perceptions of those who grew up during her chancellorship; this demographic group has been referred to *Merkelkinder* (transl. children of Merkel).
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] As a woman who is a politician from a centre-right party and also a scientist, Merkel has been compared by many in the English-language press to 20th-century British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Thatcher also had a science degree from Oxford University in chemistry.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Some have referred to her as "Iron Lady", "Iron Girl", and even "The Iron Frau", all alluding to Thatcher, whose nickname was "The Iron Lady".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Political commentators have debated the precise extent to which their agendas are similar.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Later in her tenure, Merkel acquired the nickname *"Mutti"* (a German familiar form of "mother").
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] She has also been called the "Iron Chancellor", in reference to Otto von Bismarck.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] In 1977, at the age of 23, Merkel, then Angela Kasner, married physics student Ulrich Merkel (born 1953) and took his surname.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Her second and current husband is quantum chemist and professor Joachim Sauer, who has largely avoided media attention during and after Merkel's political career.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] They first met in 1981 and married in 1998.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel has no children, but Sauer has two adult sons from a previous marriage.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Having grown up in East Germany, Merkel learned Russian at school.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] She was able to speak informally to Vladimir Putin in Russian but conducted diplomatic dialogue through an interpreter.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] She rarely spoke English in public, but delivered a small section of an address to the British Parliament in English in 2014.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel is a fervent football fan and was known to listen to games while in the Bundestag and to attend games of the national team in her official capacity, including Germany's 1–0 victory against Argentina in the 2014 World Cup Final.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel has stated that her favorite film is *The Legend of Paul and Paula*, an East German movie released in 1973.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel has a fear of dogs, which developed after she was attacked by one in 1995.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Vladimir Putin brought in his Labrador Retriever during a press conference in 2007.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Putin claims he did not mean to scare her, though Merkel later observed, "I understand why he has to do this – to prove he's a man. ...
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Since 2017, Merkel has occasionally been seen shaking visibly on several public occasions, recovering shortly afterwards.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] After one such occasion, she attributed the shaking to dehydration, saying that she felt better after a drink of water.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] In September 2021, after evading the question for most of her career, Merkel said that she considered herself a feminist.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] The statement came in a conference along with Nigerian writer and feminist Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Since her retirement, Merkel has commented on the Russo-Ukrainian war, but has otherwise limited her involvement in political matters.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] She has instead focused on travelling, attending only "feel-good events" (*Wohlfühltermine*) in a private capacity.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] President Donald Trump, according to *Politico*, citing a forthcoming book by Jonathan Karl.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] The EKBO is a member of the Union of Protestant Churches in the EKD.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Before the 2004 merger of the Evangelical Church in Berlin-Brandenburg and the Evangelical Church in Silesian Upper Lusatia, Merkel belonged to the former.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] In 2012, Merkel said, regarding her faith: "I am a member of the Protestant Church.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] I believe in God and religion is also my constant companion, and has been for the whole of my life.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] We as Christians should above all not be afraid of standing up for our beliefs." She also publicly declared that Germany suffers not from "too much Islam" but "too little Christianity".
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Since 1991, Merkel has sat annually for sitting and standing portraits by, and interview with, Herlinde Koelbl.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was portrayed by Swiss actress Anna Katarina in the 2012 political satire film *The Dictator*.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel features as a main character in two of the three plays that make up the Europeans Trilogy (*Bruges*, *Antwerp*, and *Tervuren*) by Paris-based UK playwright Nick Awde: *Bruges* (2014) and *Tervuren* (2016).
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] A character named Merkel, accompanied by a sidekick called Schäuble, also appears as the sinister female henchman in Michael Paraskos's novel *In Search of Sixpence*.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] On the American sketch-comedy series *Saturday Night Live*, Merkel has been parodied by Kate McKinnon.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] On the British sketch-comedy *Tracey Ullman's Show*, comedian Tracey Ullman has parodied Merkel to international acclaim.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] In 2016, a documentary film *Angela Merkel – The Unexpected* was produced by Broadview TV and MDR in collaboration with Arte and Das Erste.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] In 2024, a German TV show called 'Miss Merkel' reimagined her as a detective.
[src:achim-großmann/angela-merkel-p02] It is based on the bestselling novels by German writer David Safier and is a comedy that was a hit in Germany and then shown on public broadcaster RAI, dubbed into Italian.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] DB was founded after the merger between Deutsche Bundesbahn and the East German Deutsche Reichsbahn in 1994 after the unification of Germany and has been operating ever since.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Deutsche Bahn is the second-largest transport company in Germany, after the German postal and logistics company Deutsche Post / DHL.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] DB provides both long-distance and regional transport, serving around 132 million long distance passengers and 1.6 billion regional passengers in 2022.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] In 2022, DB transported 222 million tons of cargo.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The group is divided into several companies, including DB Fernverkehr (long-distance passenger), *DB Regio* (local passenger services) and *DB Cargo* (rail freight).
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The Group subsidiary *DB InfraGO* also operates large parts of the German railway infrastructure, making it the largest rail network in Europe.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The company generates about half of its total revenue from operating rail transport, with the other half of the business comprising further transport and logistics businesses, as well as various service providers.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The company generates further revenue through public transport contracts and support services for infrastructure maintenance and expansion.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The Deutsche Bahn Group is divided into various organizational units that perform their tasks with subsidiaries.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] DB Personenverkehr is the unit that manages passenger travel within Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Originally called *Reise & Touristik* (lit.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] 'Travel and Tourism'), this group is responsible for the managing, servicing and running of German passenger services.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] This group is divided into DB Fernverkehr and DB Regio.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] DB Fernverkehr AG is a semi-independent division of Deutsche Bahn that operates long-distance passenger trains in Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] It was founded in 1999 in the second stage of the privatisation of German Federal Railways under the name of DB Reise & Touristik and renamed in 2003.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] DB Fernverkehr operates all Intercity Express and Intercity trains in Germany as well as in some neighboring countries and several EuroCity and EuroCityExpress trains throughout Europe.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Unlike its sister companies DB Regio and DB Cargo, DB Fernverkehr still holds a *de facto* monopoly in its segment of the market as it operates hundreds of trains per day, while all competitors' long-distance services combined amount to no more than 10–15 trains per day.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] DB Fernverkehr operated a few long-distance coach services throughout Germany, called *IC Bus*, which since have been terminated.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] DB Regio AG is the subsidiary of Deutsche Bahn that operates passenger trains on short and medium distances in Germany.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Unlike its long-distance counterpart, DB Fernverkehr, it does not operate trains on its own account.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Traffic is ordered and paid for by the Bundesländer (states) or their respective regional train operation supervisors.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Some states have awarded long-term contracts to DB Regio (usually 10 to 15 years), in others, DB Regio's operations are decreasing, in North Rhine-Westphalia, their market share is expected to be lower than 50%.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The bus services consist of 25 bus companies, which have subsidiary companies themselves.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The Transport and Logistics division acted in the market with the business units DB Schenker and DB Cargo, which were combined under the umbrella of DB Schenker, and the Intermodal division, which operates in combined transport.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] In 2016, rail freight transport was separated from logistics and DB Schenker Rail was renamed DB Cargo.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] In cooperation with the logistics provider time:matters, DB also offers the transport of shipments weighing up to 20 kg (44 lb) on its EC/IC/ICE trains.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The infrastructure division was divided into the DB Netz (rail infrastructure), DB Station&Service (stations and services) and DB Energie (energy) business units.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] At the end of December 2023, DB Netz merged with DB Station&Service to create DB InfraGO AG.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The new company is intended to reduce poor communication between the two previously separate infrastructure firms.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] DB Engineering & Consulting, which is responsible for construction supervision, construction planning and maintenance, is also assigned to this department without being part of a business area.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The California High-Speed Rail Authority's (CHSRA) board approved on 15 November 2017 an early train operator contract with DB Engineering & Consulting USA.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The firm is the U.S. arm of Deutsche Bahn AG.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] As early train operator, DB Engineering & Consulting will assist CHSRA with planning, designing and implementing the state's high-speed rail program.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] DB also has interests abroad, owning the United Kingdom's largest rail freight operator, DB Cargo UK, which also operates the British Royal Train and also has interests in Eastern Europe.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] It is possible to obtain train times for any journey in Europe from Deutsche Bahn's website.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Trans-Eurasia Logistics is a joint venture with Russian Railways (RŽD) that operates container freight trains between Germany and China via Russia.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The railway network in Germany dates back to 1835 when the first tracks were laid on a 6 km (3.7 mi) route between Nuremberg and Fürth.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The Deutsche Reichsbahn operated from 1920 through the Weimar and Nazi eras until 1949, when it was split between East and West Germany into two successor entities, Deutsche Reichsbahn and Deutsche Bundesbahn, respectively.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] They remained separate throughout the Cold War era division of Germany, and joined after the 1989 fall of the Berlin Wall, and German reunification in 1990.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] On 1 January 1994 Deutsche Reichsbahn and Deutsche Bundesbahn were merged to form one company, Deutsche Bahn, the successor organisation to the Reichsbahn.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] At the same time, Deutsche Bahn adopted its current logo and *DB* abbreviation.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Kurt Weidemann modernised the logo and typographer Erik Spiekermann designed a new corporate font known as DB Type.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] When Deutsche Bahn was formed in January 1994, it became a joint stock-company, and was designed to operate the railways of both the former East and West Germany after unification in October 1990 as a single, uniform, and private company.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] There are three main periods of development in this unified German railway: its formation, its early years (1994–1999), and the period from 1999 to the present.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Originally, DBAG had its head office in Frankfurt am Main but moved to Potsdamer Platz in central Berlin in 1996, where it occupies a 26-storey office tower designed by Helmut Jahn at the eastern end of the Sony Centre and named Bahntower.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] As the lease was to expire in 2010, DB had announced plans to relocate to Berlin Hauptbahnhof, and in 2007 a proposal for a new head office by 3XN Architects won an architectural competition which also included Foster + Partners, *Dominique Perrault* and Auer + Weber.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] However, these plans were put on hold due to the 2008 financial crisis, and the Bahntower lease was extended.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Construction of the new head office building was started in 2017 under the title "Cube Berlin" according to the designs by 3XN.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Finished in February 2020, the Cube will house the legal offices of Deutsche Bahn, but not become the main head office.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The second step of the Bahnreform (railway reform) was carried out in 1999.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] All rolling stock, track, personnel, and real assets were divided between the subsidiaries of DBAG: DB Reise & Touristik AG (long-distance passenger service, later renamed DB Station & Service AG (operating the stations)).
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] This new organisational scheme was introduced not least to implement European Community directive 91/440/EEC that requires open access operations on railway lines by companies other than those that own the rail infrastructure.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] In December 2007, DB reorganised again, bringing all passenger services into its DB Bahn arm, logistics under DB Schenker and infrastructure and operations under DB Netze.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The DB is owned by the Federal Republic.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] By the Constitution, the Federal Republic is required to retain (directly or indirectly) a majority of the infrastructure (the present DB Netze) stocks.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] In 2008, it was agreed to "float" a portion of the business, meaning an end to the 100% share the German Federal Republic had in it, with a plan that 25% of the overall share would be sold to the private sector.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] However the onset of the 2008 financial crisis saw this cancelled.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] In June 2018 controversy grew in the United Kingdom over widespread cancellations of railway services and numerous delayed services operated by Deutsche Bahn in Britain, under its Northern brand.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] This resulted in Britain's Minister of Transport, Chris Grayling, setting up an enquiry into whether the Deutsche Bahn subsidiary had breached its contractual agreement to provide railway services in the north of England.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] In 2024, Deutsche Bahn faced significant operational challenges during the Euro 2024 football tournament, including frequent train delays, cancellations, and infrastructure issues.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] The rail carrier reported a €1 billion half year net loss stemming from investments to repair its rail network, strikes and bad weather in July of the same year.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] As a result, Deutsche Bahn announced that they would shed 30,000 administrative jobs, roughly equal to 9% of their workforce.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] In September 2024, the company came to an agreement with DSV of Denmark, a logistics company; in the agreement, DSV will acquire Schenker from Deutsche Bahn for $15.84 billion.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] There are several other operators in Germany which sometimes offer other categories, also, a local transport authority or tariff associations might brand the trains in a different way than DB does.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] For example, in the Nuremberg region, RE and RB trains are not differentiated, but called R instead.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] In some regions, such as Verkehrsverbund Berlin-Brandenburg, private operators do use the RE and RB labels, in others, such as Saxony, they do not.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Ticket prices generally rise degressively over distance, particularly for Sparpreise and Supersparpreise.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Seat reservations are included only for first class *Flexpreis* tickets and seating capacity without reservation is not assured, even for tickets valid on one particular connection only.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Local trains (S, RB, RE, IRE) also accept tickets issued by local transport associations, which can also be used on buses, trams, and U-Bahn trains.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Other special tickets, such as the Länder-Tickets ("state tickets"), which give unlimited journeys on local trains and in many transport associations within a state, and Interrail are also available.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] These tickets offer group tickets, where up to five people can travel on a single ticket.
[src:achim-großmann/deutsche-bahn] Deutsche Bahn sponsored the German football club Hertha BSC between 2006 and 2015.
